ysia}}\n\n[[Category:Failed amendments of the Constitution of Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Formation of Malaysia]]\n[[Category:History of Malaysia]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox legislation\n|short_title         = Constitution (Amendment) Bill 2019\n|legislature         = [[Parliament of Malaysia]]\n|image               = \n|imagesize           = \n|imagealt            = \n|caption             = \n|long_title          = A Bill intituled an Act to amend the Federal Constitution.\n|territorial_extent  = [[Malaysia]]\n|considered_by       = [[Dewan Rakyat]]\n|bill_citation       = D.R 7/2019\n|bill_date           = \n|introduced_by       = [[Liew Vui Keong]]\n|1st_reading         = 4 April 2019\n|2nd_reading         = 9 April 2019\n|3rd_reading         = \n|committee_report    = \n|white_paper         = \n|amends              = [[Constitution of Malaysia]]\n|related_legislation = Constitution (Amendment) Act 1976\n|summary             = To restore the constitutional status of [[Sabah]] and [[Sarawak]] according to the [[Malaysia Agreement]].\n|keywords            = \n|status              = Not passed\n}}\n{{History of Malaysia}}\n\nOn 4 April 2019, a [[Bill (law)|bill]] '''proposing an [[Constitutional amendment|amendment]] to the [[Constitution of Malaysia]]''' was [[Table (parliamentary procedure)|tabled]] in the [[Dewan Rakyat]] of the [[Parliament of Malaysia]]. The bill proposes to [[constitutional amendment|amend]] Article 1(2) so as to restore the status of the two [[East Malaysia]]n states of [[Sabah]] and [[Sarawak]] according to the original content of [[Malaysia Agreement]] that was signed in 1963.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/09/16/key-points-from-the-malaysia-agreement-1963-1-unlike-malaysian-laws-ma63-cannot-be-changed-in-the-ma/|title=Key points from the Malaysia Agreement 1963|work=The Star|date=16 September 2018|accessdate=4 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404171113/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/09/16/key-points-from-the-malaysia-agreement-1963-1-unlike-malaysian-laws-ma63-cannot-be-changed-in-the-ma/|archive-date=4 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"MA63 restoration means\">{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/what-restoring-ma63-rights-means|title=What restoring MA63 rights means|publisher=The Straits Times|date=18 September 2018|accessdate=4 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404144802/https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/what-restoring-ma63-rights-means|archivedate=4 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"MA63 restoration\">{{cite web|url=https://cilisos.my/sabah-and-sarawak-may-no-longer-be-known-as-states-but-how-is-this-gonna-work/|title=Sabah and Sarawak may no longer be known as states. But how is this gonna work?|author=Sabrina Noor|publisher=Cilisos.my|date=15 March 2019|accessdate=4 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190319101229/https://cilisos.my/sabah-and-sarawak-may-no-longer-be-known-as-states-but-how-is-this-gonna-work/|archive-date=19 March 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nDespite six hours of debate in the Parliament during the second reading of the bill on 9 April,<ref name=\"six hours debate\">{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/04/09/debate-on-constitution-amendment-bill-lasts-more-than-six-hours/1741517|title=Debate on Constitution (Amendment) Bill lasts more than six hours|work=Bernama|publisher=The Malay Mail|date=9 April 2019|accessdate=10 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190410030204/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/04/09/debate-on-constitution-amendment-bill-lasts-more-than-six-hours/1741517|archivedate=10 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"failure of passage forever remembered in history\">{{cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asia/sabah-sarawak-equal-partners-bill-fails-to-get-two-thirds-11428450|title=Bill to make Sabah, Sarawak equal partners rejected in Malaysia parliament|work=Bernama|publisher=Channel NewsAsia|date=10 April 2019|accessdate=10 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190410084211/https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asia/sabah-sarawak-equal-partners-bill-fails-to-get-two-thirds-11428450|archivedate=10 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> only 138 [[Member of parliament|MPs]] supported the bill, 10 votes short of the two-thirds majority of the chamber, 148 votes, required for amendments to the Constitution. The remaining 59 (non-absent) votes were abstentions, all of which are from [[Opposition (Malaysia)|opposition]] parties.<ref name=\"UMNO/BN abstained in the voting process\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bharian.com.my/berita/nasional/2019/04/551001/umnobn-punca-pindaan-ruu-ma63-tidak-diluluskan-anwar|title=UMNO/BN punca pindaan RUU MA63 tidak diluluskan - Anwar|trans-title=UMNO/BN caused amendment of the MA63 bill to fail - Anwar|author=Mohd Anwar Patho Rohman|language=ms|publisher=Berita Harian|date=10 April 2019|accessdate=10 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"no two-thirds majority\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theedgemarkets.com/article/no-twothirds-majority-bill-make-sabah-sarawak-equal-partners|title=No two-thirds majority for Bill to make Sabah, Sarawak equal partners|author=Adam Aziz|publisher=The Edge Markets|date=9 April 2019|accessdate=10 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190410021305/https://www.theedgemarkets.com/article/no-twothirds-majority-bill-make-sabah-sarawak-equal-partners|archivedate=10 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/04/09/pakatans-federal-constitution-amendment-on-sabah-sarawak-foiled/1741510|title=Pakatan's Federal Constitution amendment on Sabah, Sarawak foiled|author=Yiswaree Palansamy|publisher=The Malay Mail|date=9 April 2019|accessdate=10 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190410044737/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/04/09/pakatans-federal-constitution-amendment-on-sabah-sarawak-foiled/1741510|archivedate=10 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Sabah Sarawak status stays following amendment failure\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/133634/status-of-sabah-sarawak-stays/|title=Status of Sabah, Sarawak stays|work=Bernama|publisher=Daily Express|date=10 April 2019|accessdate=10 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190410022521/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/133634/status-of-sabah-sarawak-stays/|archivedate=10 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n===1976 constitutional amendment===\nIn 1976, under the premiership of then-Prime Minister [[Hussein Onn]], Article 1(2) was amended as part of a larger package affecting 45 articles and 2 schedules in the [[Constitution of Malaysia]]. This package removed the distinction between the states in Peninsula Malaysia and the Bornean states of Sabah and Sarawak. It was argued, at the time, that the change would lead to greater uniformity between the eastern and western regions of Malaysia. As a result of some political maneuvering by the then Prime Minister, no MPs from Sabah or Sarawak opposed this amendment package.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaysiakini.com/news/471345|title=Sabah and Sarawak downgraded by their MPs in 1976|author=Wong Chin Huat|publisher=Malaysiakini|date=8 April 2019|accessdate=2 May 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190409060504/https://www.malaysiakini.com/news/471345|archivedate=9 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Breaches of the Malaysia Agreement===\n[[File:Sarawak for Sarawakians sticker on a car backscreen.jpg|thumbnail|A \"Sarawak for Sarawakians\" car sticker incorpoating elements of a pre-Malaysian Sarawak flag.]]\nThe 1963 [[Malaysia Agreement]], under which Sabah and Sarawak unified with [[Federation of Malaya|Malaya]] to become Malaysia, included strong provisions for the autonomy of Sabah and Sarawak (see the [[18-point agreement|18-point]] and [[20-point agreement]]). However, this autonomy has eroded in numerous aspects, such as a smaller share of oil revenue than previously agreed and a reduction in the territorial waters that belonged to each state. Following their victory in the 2018 election, the Pakatan Harapan alliance promised to make changes including an amendment to Article (1)2 and a greater share of oil revenue.<ref name=\"MA63 restoration means\"/><ref name=\"MA63 restoration\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2017/12/08/ma63-igc-report-set-up-terms-for-three-sovereign-states-to-form-malaysia/|title=MA63, IGC Report set up terms for three sovereign states to form Malaysia|author=Philip Kiew|publisher=The Borneo Post|date=8 December 2017|accessdate=5 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190405064248/https://www.theborneopost.com/2017/12/08/ma63-igc-report-set-up-terms-for-three-sovereign-states-to-form-malaysia/|archivedate=5 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/09/16/the-malaysia-agreement-disagreement/|title=The Malaysia Agreement disagreement|work=The Star|date=16 September 2018|accessdate=4 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404170329/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/09/16/the-malaysia-agreement-disagreement/|archive-date=4 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>{{sfn|Popelier|2019|p=324}} Other causes of dispute between East and West Malaysia include [[freedom of religion]],<ref name=\"religious freedom issues\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/news/world/332044/sarawak-group-calls-for-independence|title=Sarawak group calls for independence|publisher=Bangkok Post|date=22 January 2013|accessdate=4 April 2019}}</ref> distribution of profits from [[natural resources]],{{sfn|Harding|2012|p=95}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/02/25/ma63-federal-constitution-infringed-upon-since-formation-of-msia-former-rep/|title=MA63, Federal Constitution infringed upon since formation of M'sia \u2014 Former rep|publisher=The Borneo Post|date=25 February 2019|accessdate=4 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404085038/https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/02/25/ma63-federal-constitution-infringed-upon-since-formation-of-msia-former-rep/|archivedate=4 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[demographic change]] ([[Demographics of Sabah#Mass conversion and autonomy in freedom of religion issues|particularly in Sabah]]).{{sfn|Sadiq|2008|p=83}}{{sfn|Harding|Chin|2014|p=173}}{{sfn|Weiss|2014|p=97}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thediplomat.com/2019/04/whats-behind-calls-for-independence-in-sabah/|title=What's Behind Calls for Independence in Sabah?|author=Piya Sukhani|publisher=The Diplomat|date=3 April 2019|accessdate=4 April 2019|url-access=subscription|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403142144/https://thediplomat.com/2019/04/whats-behind-calls-for-independence-in-sabah/|archive-date=3 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nPrior to 2010, the anniversary of Federation was a public holiday in only the East Malaysian states, but it was later made a national holiday by the government in response to an opposition statement declaring their intention to do so if they won an election.<ref name=\"wasn't until\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/09/16/malaysia-day-special/|title=Malaysia Day Special - New Hope, New Challenges|work=The Star|date=16 September 2018|accessdate=4 April 2019|quote=Malaysia may have been formed in 1963, but believe it or not, it wasn't until 2010 that Malaysia Day was celebrated as a national public holiday. Prior to that, it was a state holiday only in Sabah and Sarawak.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404092704/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/09/16/malaysia-day-special/|archive-date=4 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Some groups, including the Borneo Heritage Foundation (BHF), Movement for Change Sarawak (MoCS), and the Sarawak Association of People's Aspirations (SAPA), have cited these issues, among others, as reasons for advocating [[List of active separatist movements in Asia#Malaysia|separation from Malaysia]].<ref name=\"religious freedom issues\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.therakyatpost.com/news/2014/02/16/many-in-sabah-sarawak-dont-want-to-be-part-of-malaysia-claims-analyst/|title=Many in Sabah, Sarawak don't want to be part of Malaysia, claims analyst|publisher=The Rakyat Post|date=16 February 2014|accessdate=4 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404105722/http://www.therakyatpost.com/news/2014/02/16/many-in-sabah-sarawak-dont-want-to-be-part-of-malaysia-claims-analyst/|archivedate=4 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2014/08/13/group-draws-up-self-determination-petition-for-sarawak-and-sabah/|title=Group draws up self determination petition for Sarawak and Sabah|publisher=The Borneo Post|date=13 August 2014|accessdate=4 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404105522/https://www.theborneopost.com/2014/08/13/group-draws-up-self-determination-petition-for-sarawak-and-sabah/|archivedate=4 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ style=\"text-align: center;\" | [[Malaysia Agreement|1963 Malaysia Agreement]] (MA63)\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Authority of<br />{{flag|Sabah}}<br />{{flag|Sarawak}} !! scope=\"col\" | MA63 as agreed between<br />{{flag|United Kingdom}}, {{flag|Malaya}}, {{flagicon image|Flag of North Borneo (1948\u20131963).svg}} [[Crown Colony of North Borneo|North Borneo]], {{flagicon image|Flag of Sarawak (1946\u20131963).svg}} [[Crown Colony of Sarawak|Sarawak]], {{flagicon image|Flag of Singapore (1946-1959).svg}} [[Colony of Singapore|Singapore]] !! scope=\"col\" | Current situation under<br />{{flag|Malaysia}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Development\n| British delegation promised both states a total of [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]1\u00bd million a year for five years after [[Malaysia Day]], provided the [[Federation of Malaya|Malayan]] government also extended aid for that period.{{sfn|Silcock|1963|p=54}} Malaya would provide [[Malaya and British Borneo dollar|$]]200 million to [[Crown Colony of North Borneo|North Borneo]] and $300 million to [[Crown Colony of Sarawak|Sarawak]] for the first five years of Malaysia,{{sfn|Silcock|1963|p=53}} while [[Colony of Singapore|Singapore]] would provide a $150 million development loan to North Borneo and Sarawak, of which $100 million would be interest-free for five years<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/history/events/7fdd00ed-603e-47e0-8e08-f6499d385404|title=Signing of the Malaysia Agreement|via=National Library Board, Singapore|date=9 July 1963|accessdate=5 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190405041605/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/history/events/7fdd00ed-603e-47e0-8e08-f6499d385404|archive-date=5 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19630710-1.2.17|title=Logic triumphed: It was just settlement, says Lee|work=The Straits Times|via=National Library Board, Singapore|date=10 July 1963|accessdate=5 April 2019|page=4|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180805203206/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19630710-1.2.17|archive-date=5 August 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> || [[Sabah]]: [[Malaysian ringgit|RM]]5 billion per year{{sfn|Dambul|Omar|Osman|2010|p=18}}<ref name=\"yearly budget\">{{cite web|url=https://dayakdaily.com/sarawak-still-has-to-compete-with-other-states-for-a-fair-share-in-budget-allocation/|title=Sarawak still has to 'compete' with other states for a fair share in budget allocation|author=Arnold Puyok|publisher=Dayak Daily|date=3 November 2018|accessdate=4 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190405054816/https://dayakdaily.com/sarawak-still-has-to-compete-with-other-states-for-a-fair-share-in-budget-allocation/|archivedate=5 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><br />[[Sarawak]]: RM4.3 billion per year<ref name=\"yearly budget\"/><br />(Both states are the poorest in Malaysia){{sfn|Hashim|1998|p=47}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.loyarburok.com/2011/05/09/the-root-causes-of-poverty-in-sabah-sarawak-exposed-stories-from-the-east/|title=The Root Causes of Poverty in Sabah & Sarawak, Exposed (Stories from the East)|author=Daniel John Jambun|publisher=Loyar Burok|date=9 May 2011|accessdate=9 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190409024510/https://www.loyarburok.com/2011/05/09/the-root-causes-of-poverty-in-sabah-sarawak-exposed-stories-from-the-east/|archivedate=9 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://says.com/my/news/pkr-says-barisan-nasional-keeps-sabah-and-sarawak-poor-to-control-them|title=Why Are Sabah And Sarawak So Poor, When Both Are Rich In Natural Resources?|author=Mei Mei Chu|publisher=Says.com|date=27 November 2013|accessdate=9 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190409024242/https://says.com/my/news/pkr-says-barisan-nasional-keeps-sabah-and-sarawak-poor-to-control-them|archivedate=9 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.borneotoday.net/resolve-or-dissolve-malaysia-sabah-sarawak-lags-far-behind-peninsula/|title=Resolve or Dissolve Malaysia; Sabah, Sarawak Lags Far Behind Peninsula|publisher=Borneo Today|date=8 June 2017|accessdate=5 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190405055228/https://www.borneotoday.net/resolve-or-dissolve-malaysia-sabah-sarawak-lags-far-behind-peninsula/|archivedate=5 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Education\n| Rights to own education system{{#tag:ref|Education, while becoming a federal subject in principle, is to remain practically under state control until the state government otherwise decides; in particular, the present policy of teaching in English is to continue.{{sfn|Silcock|1963|p=53}}|group=\"note\"}} || [[Education in Malaysia|Malaysia standardised education system]]<br />(Dilapidated schools and frequent misinformation in history textbooks for both [[History of Sabah|Sabah]] and [[History of Sarawak|Sarawak]] history)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.themalaysianinsight.com/s/14712|title=Historian on mission to correct textbooks on Sabah, Sarawak|author=Jason Santos|publisher=The Malaysian Insight|date=15 September 2017|accessdate=4 April 2019|url-access=subscription|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170915031907/https://www.themalaysianinsight.com/s/14712/|archive-date=15 September 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/metro/metro-news/2018/11/14/more-than-1000-schools-still-in-dilapidated-category/|title=More than 1,000 schools still in dilapidated category|author=Sharon Ling|work=The Star|date=14 November 2018|accessdate=5 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181118214132/https://www.thestar.com.my/metro/metro-news/2018/11/14/more-than-1000-schools-still-in-dilapidated-category/|archive-date=18 November 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2018/10/21/more-than-half-of-sabah-schools-dilapidated/|title=More than half of Sabah schools dilapidated|work=Bernama|publisher=Free Malaysia Today|date=21 October 2018|accessdate=5 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190405060350/https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2018/10/21/more-than-half-of-sabah-schools-dilapidated/|archivedate=5 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Immigration\n| Control immigration entry{{#tag:ref|Immigration to remain largely under state control; while the federation is to have general control of movement in and out of Malaysia and between states, entry into the Borneo states will require the approval of the state concerned, and except that the federal government may bar entry in the national interest, the Borneo states are to have discretion in permitting entry by persons outside Malaysia.{{sfn|Silcock|1963|p=53}} On [[citizenship]], through\nthe [[Cobbold Commission]] recommendations provides additional provisions for the registration of foreign-born residents in the eight years after Malaysia.{{sfn|Silcock|1963|p=53}}|group=\"note\"}} || Controlled immigration entry via [[:wikt:permit|permit]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imi.gov.my/index.php/en/history-of-department-of-immigration.html|title=History|publisher=Immigration Department of Malaysia|accessdate=5 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180721182446/http://www.imi.gov.my/index.php/en/history-of-department-of-immigration.html|archive-date=21 July 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwc.com/gx/en/services/people-organisation/publications/assets/pwc-east-malaysia-immigration-requirements-and-practices.pdf|title=Malaysia: East Malaysia immigration requirements and practices|via=PricewaterhouseCoopers|date=20 January 2017|accessdate=5 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190405052808/https://www.pwc.com/gx/en/services/people-organisation/publications/assets/pwc-east-malaysia-immigration-requirements-and-practices.pdf|archivedate=5 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><br />([[Sabah]]: [[Refugees of the Philippines|Southern Filipino refugees]] fleeing the [[Civil conflict in the Philippines|civil war]] were issued IMM13 documents by the Federal government, instead of the Sabahan state government, leading to a situation whereby the refugees, and their families who had settled in Sabah, could not be stripped of their IMM13 without rendering them stateless as the Philippine government did not recognise them as citizens){{sfn|Sadiq|2008|p=51}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news.cfm?NewsID=128764|title=Stateless foreigners headache|publisher=Daily Express|date=17 November 2018|accessdate=5 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190405062106/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news.cfm?NewsID=128764|archivedate=5 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Language\n| [[English language|English]] as the official language{{#tag:ref|The national language of the federation will be [[Malay language|Malay]], but English is to remain an official language for ten years after [[Malaysia Day]] and thereafter till the state legislature otherwise provides.{{sfn|Silcock|1963|p=53}}|group=\"note\"}} || [[Sabah]]: [[Malay language|Malay]] is amended as official language through the controversial 1973 State Constitution<ref name=\"Sabah Constitution\">{{cite web|url=http://www.lawnet.sabah.gov.my/lawnet/SabahConstitution/PartI.htm|title=Constitution of the State of Sabah|publisher=Sabah State Government (State Attorney-General's Chambers)|accessdate=5 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160615120202/http://www.lawnet.sabah.gov.my/lawnet/SabahConstitution/PartI.htm|archivedate=15 June 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"religious liberty\">{{cite web|url=http://www.necf.org.my/newsmaster.cfm?&menuid=2&action=view&retrieveid=1011|title=Religious Liberty in East Malaysia|author=David Phung|publisher=NECF Malaysia Religious Liberty Commission|accessdate=5 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190405051252/http://www.necf.org.my/newsmaster.cfm?&menuid=2&action=view&retrieveid=1011|archivedate=5 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><br />[[Sarawak]]: Both Malay and English are official language as of 2015<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2015/11/18/sarawak-makes-english-official-language-along-with-bm/1007033|title=Sarawak makes English official language along with BM|author=Sulok Tawie|publisher=The Malay Mail|date=18 November 2015|accessdate=5 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190405052059/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2015/11/18/sarawak-makes-english-official-language-along-with-bm/1007033|archivedate=5 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><br />(Malay is also used in all courts except High Court and Native Court)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Law\n| Authority to agree/disagree to amend law{{#tag:ref|On the special position of the indigenous race, it adopts the recommendations of the Malayan members of the commission and provides that in the federal public service as well as within the states, the Borneo indigenous are to enjoy the special rights and privileges that Malay now enjoy under the present constitution.{{sfn|Silcock|1963|p=53}} In matters concerning land administration the powers of the federation ''[[:wikt:vis-\u00e0-vis|vis-\u00e0-vis]]'' the states are to be modified to give the states the power to decide whether or not to follow the policies formulated in the National Land Council.{{sfn|Silcock|1963|p=53}} The Borneo states are to have a total of 40 seats in the Federal House of Representatives \u2013 24 to Sarawak and 16 to North Borneo. No reduction in the proportion of their representation to the whole (except by reason of the entry of new states) may take place in the seven years after Malaysia without the concurrence of the government of the state concerned, and thereafter any change in proportion must be supported by a two-thirds majority in each House of Parliament.{{sfn|Silcock|1963|p=54}}|group=\"note\"}} || Recognised as state under [[Law of Malaysia|Malaysian laws]] with the exclusion of certain laws (e.g. [[National Land Code (Malaysia)|National Land Code]])<br />(Frequent reported conflicts with federal government regarding [[aboriginal title|indigenous land rights]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eprints.utm.my/id/eprint/5026/|title=Conflict in the Land Law under the Federation Structure|author=Adibah Awang|work=International Convention on Urban Development & Management|publisher=Universiti Teknologi Malaysia|year=2003|accessdate=8 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190408040532/http://eprints.utm.my/id/eprint/5026/|archive-date=8 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news.cfm?NewsID=131697|title=Prof: Respect indigenous land rights|author=David Thien|publisher=Daily Express|date=27 February 2019|accessdate=8 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190408035826/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news.cfm?NewsID=131697|archivedate=8 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Natural resources\n| [[Crown Colony of North Borneo|North Borneo]]: 40% of the state revenue{{sfn|Wilson|1996|p=57}}<br />[[Crown Colony of Sarawak|Sarawak]]: Up to RM21 million for the first four years<br />(Both North Borneo and Sarawak retain import duty, [[excise]] duty and export duty with North Borneo retain a total of 30% from customs and excise for as long it is responsible for health and medical expenditure){{#tag:ref|On finance, it is agreed that the level of federal [[taxation]] in the states should be brought up to federal levels over a period of years, and that in addition to the sources of revenue at present allocated to states, North Borneo and Sarawak should retain import duty and excise duty on [[petroleum]] products, export duty on [[timber]] and other forest produce, and export duty on minerals up to a joint total of royalty and export duty of 10 per cent ''[[ad valorem]]''; and that in the case of North Borneo the state should retain a total of 30 per cent of revenue from customs and excise for as long as it is responsible for health and medical expenditure. In addition to the [[capitation (healthcare)|capitation]] and road grants received by states under the existing constitution, North Borneo and Sarawak are to receive balancing grant equal to the difference between assigned state revenue in 1963 (including statutory grants) and the estimated cost of services; Sarawak is to receive an escalating annual grant in order to assure adequate expansion of state services,\nand a special grant is also to be assigned to North Borneo, proportionate to the increase in federal revenue from that state in 1963. (These grants are to be subject to review in the first ten years after Malaysia).{{sfn|Silcock|1963|p=53}}|group=\"note\"}} || In 1966, the Continental Shelf Act was enforced by the federal government on the two despite both had already extended their jurisdiction over the [[continental shelf]] adjacent to their territory.{{sfn|Chin|Choi|1998|p=273}} Further in 1974, the Petroleum Development Act was enforced on the two, giving them only 5% of oil royalty from the [[oil revenue|revenue]]{{sfn|Lim|2008|p=75}}{{sfn|Kaur|2016|p=203}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2016/11/17/why-the-petroleum-development-act-1974-is-in-breach-of-the-malaysia-agreement-1963-and-the-federal-constitution-and-is-null-and-void/|title=Why the petroleum development Act 1974 is in breach of the Malaysia agreement 1963 and the federal constitution and is null and void|publisher=The Borneo Post|date=17 November 2016|accessdate=5 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190405041805/https://www.theborneopost.com/2016/11/17/why-the-petroleum-development-act-1974-is-in-breach-of-the-malaysia-agreement-1963-and-the-federal-constitution-and-is-null-and-void/|archivedate=5 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Religion\n| No official religion{{#tag:ref|[[Islam in Malaysia|Islam]] remains the religion of the federation, but is not to be established as the [[state religion]] in either territory, and the Borneo States are not to be required to contribute to financial aid for Muslim institutions or education, either in the states or in the federation.{{sfn|Silcock|1963|p=53}}|group=\"note\"}} || [[Sabah]]: [[Islam]] is amended as official religion through the controversial 1973 State Constitution<ref name=\"Sabah Constitution\"/><ref name=\"religious liberty\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://journalarticle.ukm.my/420/1/1.pdf|title=The Politics of centre-state conflict: the Sabah experience under the ruling Sabah Alliance (1963\u20131976)|author=Mohammad Agus Yusoff|publisher=Universiti Kebangsaan Malaysia|year=1999|accessdate=5 April 2019|page=14/25|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171104113624/http://journalarticle.ukm.my/420/1/1.pdf|archivedate=4 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><br />[[Sarawak]]: No official religion (Updated in state government website as of 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2015/12/11/islam-no-more-official-religion-on-sarawak-government-website/1021603|title=Islam no more official religion on Sarawak government website|author=Sulok Tawie|publisher=The Malay Mail|date=11 December 2015|accessdate=5 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190405043603/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2015/12/11/islam-no-more-official-religion-on-sarawak-government-website/1021603|archivedate=5 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2018, Sarawak began to allow [[religious conversion|converts]] to [[Apostasy in Islam|renounce Islam]] if they already wish so without the need to keep forcing them to stay in the religion)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/sarawak-could-allow-converts-to-renounce-islam|title=Sarawak could allow converts to renounce Islam|author=Trinna Leong|publisher=The Straits Times|date=5 March 2018|accessdate=6 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406051658/https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/sarawak-could-allow-converts-to-renounce-islam|archivedate=6 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><br />(Frequent cases of Sabahan and Sarawakians non-Muslims identified as Muslims,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.therakyatpost.com/news/2014/08/15/sabah-christians-often-mistaken-muslims-carrying-bin-binti-mykad/|title=Sabah Christians often mistaken as Muslims for carrying 'bin' or 'binti' in MyKad|author=Sandra Sokial|publisher=The Rakyat Post|date=15 August 2014|accessdate=4 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190405042610/http://www.therakyatpost.com/news/2014/08/15/sabah-christians-often-mistaken-muslims-carrying-bin-binti-mykad/|archivedate=5 April 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/read.cfm?NewsID=2026|title=Don't mess with religion|author=Richard Joe Jimmy|publisher=Daily Express|date=7 May 2016|accessdate=4 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190405042533/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/read.cfm?NewsID=2026|archivedate=5 April 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref> Muslims who wish to convert out of Islam are being prevented as well the rampant religious intolerance and conversion of non-Muslims students in schools without their parents consent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2011/01/01/sabah-apostates-repent-or-go-to-jail/|title=Sabah apostates: Repent or go to 'jail'|publisher=Free Malaysia Today|date=12 January 2011|accessdate=5 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170618040556/http://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2011/01/01/sabah-apostates-repent-or-go-to-jail/|archivedate=18 June 2017|url-status=dead}}<br />{{*}} {{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2014/07/12/path-to-leave-islam-simple-but-far-from-easy/704859|title=Path to leave Islam simple, but far from easy|author=Ida Lim|publisher=The Malay Mail|date=12 July 2014|accessdate=5 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190405044602/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2014/07/12/path-to-leave-islam-simple-but-far-from-easy/704859|archivedate=5 April 2019|url-status=live}}<br />{{*}} {{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2015/02/09/sabah-leaders-conversion-answers/|title=Sabah leaders demand explanation for underaged girl's conversion|work=The Star|date=9 February 2015|accessdate=5 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170920002110/http://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2015/02/09/sabah-leaders-conversion-answers/|archive-date=20 September 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}<br />{{*}} {{cite web|url=https://sg.news.yahoo.com/sabah-school-conversion-row-must-held-accountable-father-230600994.html|title=Sabah school in conversion row must be held accountable, father insists|work=The Malay Mail|publisher=Yahoo! News|date=26 March 2015|accessdate=5 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190405044429/https://sg.news.yahoo.com/sabah-school-conversion-row-must-held-accountable-father-230600994.html|archivedate=5 April 2019|url-status=dead}}<br />{{*}} {{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/opinion/columnists/on-the-beat/2015/04/05/teach-not-convert-students/|title=Teach, not convert students|author=Wong Chun Wai|work=The Star|date=5 April 2015|accessdate=5 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170920001958/http://www.thestar.com.my/opinion/columnists/on-the-beat/2015/04/05/teach-not-convert-students/|archive-date=20 September 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}<br />{{*}} {{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2015/08/23/in-sabah-shivers-of-discomfit-over-rising-religious-barriers/956473|title=In Sabah, shivers of discomfit over rising religious barriers|author=Julia Chan|publisher=The Malay Mail|date=23 August 2015|accessdate=5 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190405045032/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2015/08/23/in-sabah-shivers-of-discomfit-over-rising-religious-barriers/956473|archivedate=5 April 2019|url-status=live}}<br />{{*}} {{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2017/02/11/law-is-silent-on-muslim-converts-wishing-to-leave-islam-baru/|title=Law is silent on Muslim converts wishing to leave Islam \u2013 Baru|publisher=The Borneo Post|date=11 February 2017|accessdate=5 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190405043228/https://www.theborneopost.com/2017/02/11/law-is-silent-on-muslim-converts-wishing-to-leave-islam-baru/|archivedate=5 April 2019|url-status=live}}<br />{{*}} {{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news.cfm?NewsID=111622|title=Churches: Louder calls to restore religious freedom|publisher=Daily Express|date=28 July 2016|accessdate=5 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190405044214/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news.cfm?NewsID=111622|archivedate=5 April 2019|url-status=live}}<br />{{*}} {{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/crime-courts/2018/02/339414/updated-federal-court-rejects-appeal-sarawakian-apostates|title=(Updated) Federal Court rejects appeal of Sarawakian apostates|author=Goh Pei Pei|publisher=New Straits Times|date=27 February 2018|accessdate=5 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228082504/https://www.nst.com.my/news/crime-courts/2018/02/339414/updated-federal-court-rejects-appeal-sarawakian-apostates|archive-date=28 February 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In July 2006, state ''[[mufti]]'' of Sabah issued a ''[[fatwa]]'' to an ongoing [[Taoism|Taoist]] statue project where a stop-work order was then being imposed by the state government on the construction of [[Mazu (goddess)|Mazu]] (Goddess of the Sea) statue in [[Kudat District]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asianews.it/news-en/Taoist-statue-deemed-%E2%80%9Coffensive%E2%80%9D-to-Islam-raises-new-controversy-over-religious-freedom-11163.html|title=Taoist statue deemed \"offensive\" to Islam raises new controversy over religious freedom|publisher=AsiaNews.it|date=1 April 2008|accessdate=5 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190405161107/http://www.asianews.it/news-en/Taoist-statue-deemed-%E2%80%9Coffensive%E2%80%9D-to-Islam-raises-new-controversy-over-religious-freedom-11163.html|archive-date=5 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"restricted religious freedom\">{{cite web|url=http://www.necf.org.my/newsmaster.cfm?&menuid=2&action=view&retrieveid=993|title=State Spot [Sabah]|publisher=NECF Malaysia Religious Liberty Commission|accessdate=5 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190405160330/http://www.necf.org.my/newsmaster.cfm?&menuid=2&action=view&retrieveid=993|archivedate=5 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Further in April 2007, a local businesswoman loan application was rejected because her [[unisex]] styling business was in conflict with Islam)<ref name=\"restricted religious freedom\"/>\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\"| '''See also:''' [https://web.archive.org/web/20190405062555/http://www.lawnet.sabah.gov.my/Lawnet/ReportOfTheInterGovernmentalCommittee/IGCReport.pdf 1962 Inter-Governmental Committee (IGC) Report] and [https://web.archive.org/web/20190405065021/https://treaties.un.org/doc/publication/unts/volume%20750/volume-750-i-10760-english.pdf 1963 Malaysia Agreement]\n|}\n\n=== Inter-governmental negotiations ===\n{{Formation of Malaysia}}\nIn October 2009, then-Prime Minister [[Najib Razak]] declared that [[Malaysia Day]] would become a national holiday with the intent of promoting unity between West and East Malaysia.<ref name=\"wasn't until\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2009/10/19/malaysia-day-now-a-public-holiday-says-pm/|title=Malaysia Day now a public holiday, says PM|author=Yeng Ai Chun|work=The Star|date=19 October 2009|accessdate=4 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404092704/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2009/10/19/malaysia-day-now-a-public-holiday-says-pm/|archive-date=4 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On the Malaysia Day following his victory in the [[2018 Malaysian general election|2018 general election]], Prime Minister [[Mahathir Mohamad]] announced a commitment to restore Sabah and Sarawak as equal partners to Western Peninsula after a review of the 1963 Malaysia Agreement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/09/16/sabah-sarawak-to-be-restored-as-equal-partners-forming-malaysia-not-just-component-states-says-dr-m/|title=Sabah, Sarawak to be restored as equal partners forming Malaysia, says Dr M|author1=Stephanie Lee|author2=Fatimah Zainal|work=The Star|date=16 September 2018|accessdate=4 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404104854/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/09/16/sabah-sarawak-to-be-restored-as-equal-partners-forming-malaysia-not-just-component-states-says-dr-m/|archive-date=4 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/sabah-sarawak-to-be-restored-as-equal-partners-forming-malaysia-not-just-component|title=Sabah, Sarawak to be restored as equal partners forming Malaysia, not just component states, says PM Mahathir|work=The Star/Asia News Network|publisher=The Straits Times|date=16 September 2018|accessdate=4 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180917012801/https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/sabah-sarawak-to-be-restored-as-equal-partners-forming-malaysia-not-just-component|archivedate=17 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> That year, the [[Prime Minister's Department (Malaysia)|Prime Minister's Department]] published a special article regarding the formation of the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pmo.gov.my/MA63.pdf|title=Kupasan Sejarah Perjanjian Malaysia 1963|trans-title=Review of the History of the Malaysia Agreement 1963|language=Malay|publisher=Prime Minister's Department (Malaysia)|year=2018|accessdate=4 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404074423/http://www.pmo.gov.my/MA63.pdf|archivedate=4 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 March 2019, a meeting was held between Prime Minister Mahathir and representatives from the Sabah and Sarawak governments. Neither party identified any significant items of dispute with regards to the 1963 agreement. Items that were not resolved, such as [[stamp duty]] were to be referred to a Technical Review for detailed assessment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pmo.gov.my/2019/03/little-disagreement-between-federal-government-sabah-sarawak-on-ma63-pm/|title=Little Disagreement Between Federal Government, Sabah, Sarawak on MA63 \u2013 PM|work=Bernama|publisher=Prime Minister's Department (Malaysia)|date=5 March 2019|accessdate=4 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404114848/https://www.pmo.gov.my/2019/03/little-disagreement-between-federal-government-sabah-sarawak-on-ma63-pm/|archivedate=4 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Although some issues were unresolved, Minister of Law in the Prime Minister's Department [[Liew Vui Keong]] announced on 8 March that the [[Cabinet of Malaysia|cabinet]] had agreed to amend Article 1(2) of the Federal Constitution and that the amendment will be tabled for the next sitting of Parliament on 11 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/03/08/Cabinet-agrees-to-restore-Sabah-Sarawak-as-equal-partners/1730628|title=Cabinet agrees to restore Sabah, Sarawak as equal partners|work=Bernama|publisher=The Malay Mail|date=8 March 2019|accessdate=4 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404110010/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/03/08/Cabinet-agrees-to-restore-Sabah-Sarawak-as-equal-partners/1730628|archivedate=4 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On 11 March, the sitting of Parliament began with the amendment being the primary focus of discussion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/132226/spotlight-on-ma63-as-dewan-rakyat-convenes/|title=Spotlight on MA63 as Dewan Rakyat convenes|work=Bernama|publisher=Daily Express|date=11 March 2019|accessdate=4 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404113022/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/132226/spotlight-on-ma63-as-dewan-rakyat-convenes/|archivedate=4 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 April, Minister Liew announced that the federal government would table the amendment at the Parliamentary meeting, scheduled for the following week.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/04/02/law-minister-tabling-of-bill-on-equality-for-sabah-sarawak-in-parliament-ne/1738993|title=Law minister: Tabling of Bill on equality for Sabah, Sarawak in Parliament next week|author=Julia Chan|publisher=The Malay Mail|date=2 April 2019|accessdate=4 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403125012/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/04/02/law-minister-tabling-of-bill-on-equality-for-sabah-sarawak-in-parliament-ne/1738993|archivedate=3 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Dewan Rakyat debate ==\n\n=== First reading ===\n{{multiple image\n| footer   = (Left) A copy of the bill on the proposed amendment as retrieved on 4 April 2019. Article 1 (2) as it stands now, reads: \"The States of the Federation shall be [[Johore]], [[Kedah]], [[Kelantan]], [[Malacca]], [[Negeri Sembilan]], [[Pahang]], [[Penang]], [[Perak]], [[Perlis]], Sabah, Sarawak, [[Selangor]] and [[Terengganu]]\".<ref name=\"rushed\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2019/04/04/rushed-barebones-ma63-bill-causes-uproar-in-parliament/|title='Rushed', barebones MA63 bill causes uproar in Parliament|author1=Martin Carvalho|author2=Hemananthani Sivanandam|author3=Rahimy Rahim|author4=Tarrence Tan|work=The Star|date=4 April 2019|accessdate=4 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404064943/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2019/04/04/rushed-barebones-ma63-bill-causes-uproar-in-parliament/|archive-date=4 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><br />(Right) The bill explanatory statement.<ref name=\"rushed\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/04/04/first-reading-of-bill-seeking-to-amend-article-1-2-gets-underway/|title=[LIVE UPDATES] First reading of Bill seeking to amend Article 1 (2) gets underway|author=Lim How Pim|publisher=The Borneo Post|date=4 April 2019|accessdate=7 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190407071520/https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/04/04/first-reading-of-bill-seeking-to-amend-article-1-2-gets-underway/|archivedate=7 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| align    = left\n| image1   = Bill for the Amendment of the Article (1) 2 of the Constitution of Malaysia, p 1.jpg\n| width1   = 150\n| alt1     = Bill for the Amendment of the Article (1) 2 of the Constitution of Malaysia, p 1\n| image2   = Bill for the Amendment of the Article (1) 2 of the Constitution of Malaysia, p 2.jpg\n| width2   = 200\n| alt2     = Bill for the Amendment of the Article (1) 2 of the Constitution of Malaysia, p 2\n}}\n\nOn 4 April, before the amendment could be tabled for its first reading by Minister Liew, a number of [[Opposition (Malaysia)|opposition]] MPs from Sabah and Sarawak raised significant concerns that the proposed amendment was being pushed through without adequate consultation with East Malaysian MPs on the draft contents.<ref name=\"rushed\"/> Minister Liew responded with a statement in Parliament that the amendment would effectively change the status of Sabah and Sarawak from state into territory, once the committee completed their review of the 1963 agreement.<ref name=\"turn status\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theedgemarkets.com/article/constitution-amendment-will-turn-sabah-sarawak-territories-says-deputy-law-minister|title=Constitution amendment will turn Sabah, Sarawak into territories, says law minister|author=Adam Aziz|publisher=The Edge Markets|date=4 April 2019|accessdate=4 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190405025607/https://www.theedgemarkets.com/article/constitution-amendment-will-turn-sabah-sarawak-territories-says-deputy-law-minister|archivedate=5 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn his statement, Liew also explained that the special committee was chaired by Prime Minister Mahathir, along with the [[Chief Ministers in Malaysia|Chief Ministers]] of Sabah and Sarawak, the [[Attorney General of Malaysia|Attorney Generals]] and other high-ranking officers. However, he did not clarify why the bill should be passed before other separate amendments, which would promote greater autonomy of the two entities, were implemented.<ref name=\"turn status\"/> Despite the review and meetings, the bill was opposed after the reading,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/04/04/gps-mps-legal-experts-less-than-impressed-with-bill-to-amend-article-1-2/|title=GPS MPs, legal experts less than impressed with Bill to amend Article 1 (2)|author1=Lim How Pim|author2=Abdul Hakim Bujang|publisher=The Borneo Post|date=4 April 2019|accessdate=7 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190407072206/https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/04/04/gps-mps-legal-experts-less-than-impressed-with-bill-to-amend-article-1-2/|archivedate=7 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> with one opposition MP, [[Sim Kui Hian]] of the [[Sarawak United Peoples' Party]] (SUPP) who voted against the bill, stating in an interview that the amendment retained Sarawak as one of the 13 states of Malaysia rather than equal partner. He also stated that there was no amendment to [[Article 160 of the Constitution of Malaysia|Article 160 of the constitution]] regarding the definition of \"Federation\", which should be based on the Malaysia Agreement of 1963 instead of the Malaya Agreement of 1957.<ref name=\"totally unacceptable\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/04/04/article-1-2-amendment-bill-totally-unacceptable-to-sarawak-supp/|title=Article 1 (2) amendment Bill 'totally unacceptable' to Sarawak \u2013 SUPP|author=Churchill Edward|publisher=The Borneo Post|date=4 April 2019|accessdate=4 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190405024409/https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/04/04/article-1-2-amendment-bill-totally-unacceptable-to-sarawak-supp/|archivedate=5 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Other opposition MPs also followed suit demanding the bill be temporary retracted.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/133379/bill-tabled-amid-concern/|title=Bill tabled amid concern|publisher=Daily Express|date=5 April 2019|accessdate=11 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190411054851/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/133379/bill-tabled-amid-concern/|archivedate=11 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Second reading ===\n[[File:Article (1) 2 amendment with definition as according to the 1963 Malaysia Agreement.jpg|thumb|350px|right|The bill redefinition as announced by [[Prime Minister's Department (Malaysia)|Minister in the Prime Minister's Department for Legal Affairs]], [[Liew Vui Keong]] on 8 April 2019 for the amendment as according to the original 1963 agreement with the exclusion of [[Singapore]] which have [[Singapore in Malaysia|leaving the federation]] in 1965.<ref name=\"bill redefinition\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/04/08/liew-article-12-amendment-bills-wording-to-be-altered-to-follow-that-of-1963-version/|title=Liew: Article 1(2) amendment Bill's wording to be altered to follow that of 1963 version|author1=Lim How Pim|author2=Abdul Hakim Bujang|publisher=The Borneo Post|date=8 April 2019|accessdate=8 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190408095718/https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/04/08/liew-article-12-amendment-bills-wording-to-be-altered-to-follow-that-of-1963-version/|archive-date=8 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>]]\n\nOn 8 April, Minister Liew stated that the wording of the bill would follow the 1963 version of Article 1(2) of the Constitution. The minister also stated that he received no opposition from the Prime Minister or the federal Attorney General.<ref name=\"bill redefinition\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thesundaily.my/local/govt-intends-to-compromise-with-opposition-to-restore-sabah-sarawak-status-MX770068|title=Govt intends to compromise with opposition to restore Sabah, Sarawak status|author1=Amar Shah Mohsen|author2=Ashwin Kumar|work=The Sun|date=8 April 2019|accessdate=8 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190409023655/https://www.thesundaily.my/local/govt-intends-to-compromise-with-opposition-to-restore-sabah-sarawak-status-MX770068|archivedate=8 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> However, despite these changes,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/04/08/gps-sticks-to-its-decision-to-call-for-article-12-amendment-bill-to-be-withdrawn/|title=GPS sticks to its decision to call for Article 1(2) amendment Bill to be withdrawn|author1=Lim How Pim|author2=Abdul Hakim Bujang|publisher=The Borneo Post|date=8 April 2019|accessdate=8 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190408095744/https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/04/08/gps-sticks-to-its-decision-to-call-for-article-12-amendment-bill-to-be-withdrawn/|archive-date=8 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Fadillah Yusof]], Chief Whip of the [[Gabungan Parti Sarawak|Sarawak Parties Coalition]] (GPS), stood firm on a request that the bill be temporarily withdrawn, or referred to a select committee, for further discussion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/04/08/swak-govt-to-support-constitutional-amendment-if-it-reflects-original-intent-of-negotiating-parties/|title=S'wak govt to support constitutional amendment if it reflects 'original intent' of negotiating parties|publisher=The Borneo Post|date=8 April 2019|accessdate=8 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190408121652/https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/04/08/swak-govt-to-support-constitutional-amendment-if-it-reflects-original-intent-of-negotiating-parties/|archivedate=8 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn a speech on 9 April, during the second reading of the bill, Prime Minister Mahathir stated that the amendment was a \"starting point and [this] is an appropriate time for the [[Pakatan Harapan]] (PH) government to take the first step in realising the needs of the people in Sabah and Sarawak in line with the Malaysia Agreement 1963\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2019/04/477763/sabah-sarawak-revert-original-status-associate-members-malaysia|title=Sabah, Sarawak to revert to original status as associate members in Malaysia|author1=Syed Umar Ariff|author2=Beatrice Nita Jay|publisher=New Straits Times|date=9 April 2019|accessdate=9 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190410160653/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2019/04/477763/sabah-sarawak-revert-original-status-associate-members-malaysia|archive-date=10 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|People's Justice Party]] (PKR) President [[Anwar Ibrahim]] concurred saying the matter had undergone extensive debate and that the concerns of the people of Sabah and Sarawak were being addressed by the PH administration. He also stated that restoration of the two states was a meaningful step being undertaken by the PH government, compared to the half century of inaction by the previous Barisan Nasional government, and should not be opposed.<ref name=\"six hours debate\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2019/04/09/anwar-pakatan-will-keep-promise-to-make-sabah-sarawak-equal-partners/|title=Anwar: Pakatan will keep promise to make Sabah, Sarawak equal partners|author1=Martin Carvalho|author2=Hemananthani Sivanandam|author3=Rahimy Rahim|author4=Tarrence Tan|work=The Star|date=9 April 2019|accessdate=9 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190409192140/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2019/04/09/anwar-pakatan-will-keep-promise-to-make-sabah-sarawak-equal-partners/|archive-date=9 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn response to a question from Ketereh MP Tan Sri Annuar Musa concerning the necessity of having a select committee review the bill, Sabah Chief Minister [[Shafie Apdal]] agreed that such a review was unnecessary and would only delay other amendments that would restore other aspects of the 1963 agreement. He also refuted claims that passing of the bill would result in an \"erosion of nationhood among the people of Sabah and Sarawak\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2019/04/477786/shafie-supporting-amendment-bill-does-not-mean-no-love-malaysia|title=Shafie: Supporting amendment bill does not mean no love for Malaysia|author=Syed Umar Ariff|publisher=New Straits Times|date=9 April 2019|accessdate=9 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190410154251/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2019/04/477786/shafie-supporting-amendment-bill-does-not-mean-no-love-malaysia|archive-date=10 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==== Division result ====\nAt 10:20 pm [[Time in Malaysia|local time]], the chamber [[Division of the assembly|divided]].<ref>{{Cite Hansard|jurisdiction=Malaysia|title=Rang Undang-undang Perlembagaan (Pindaan) 2019: Bacaan Kali Yang Kedua dan Ketiga|url=https://www.parlimen.gov.my/files/hindex/pdf/DR-09042019.pdf|house=[[Dewan Rakyat]]|date=9 April 2019|page_start=197|page_end=204|speaker=[[Mohamad Ariff Md Yusof]]|position=[[Speaker of the Dewan Rakyat|Speaker]]|language=ms|trans-title=Constitution (Amendment) Bill 2019: Second and Third Readings|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190819083632/https://www.parlimen.gov.my/files/hindex/pdf/DR-09042019.pdf|archivedate=19 August 2019|url-status=live|format=PDF|no=18}}</ref> Of the 197 MPs present, 138 voted in support for the amendment while 59, primarily members of the [[Barisan Nasional]] coalition, did not cast a vote.<ref name=\"failure of passage forever remembered in history\" /><ref name=\"UMNO/BN abstained in the voting process\" /> The bill was put up for voting by Speaker [[Mohamad Ariff Md Yusof]] after a day-long debate with no MPs from either side actually opposing the restoration bill.<ref name=\"six hours debate\" /><ref name=\"Sabah Sarawak status stays following amendment failure\" />[[File:Result of the voting for the proposed Amendment of Constitution of Malaysia, 2019.svg|thumb|center|600px|Votes by each MP mapped onto their respective constituencies.]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Constitution (Amendment) Bill 2019: second reading division result\n|-\n! {{Abbr|No.|Number}}\n! Name\n! Party (coalition)\n! Constituency\n! State\n|- bgcolor=\"#D186F0\"\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{white|'''Supported (138)'''}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsabahtimes.com.my/nstweb/fullstory/30396|title=Constitutional Amendment Bill fails to get two-thirds majority support|work=Bernama|publisher=New Sabah Times|date=10 April 2019|accessdate=15 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190415084621/http://www.newsabahtimes.com.my/nstweb/fullstory/30396|archivedate=15 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1\n| [[Abdul Latiff Ahmad]]\n| [[Malaysian United Indigenous Party]] ([[Pakatan Harapan]])\n| {{pseat|Mersing}}\n| {{flag|Johor}}\n|-\n| 2\n| [[Abdul Rahim Bakri]]\n| [[Malaysian United Indigenous Party]] ([[Pakatan Harapan]])\n| {{pseat|Kudat}}\n| {{flag|Sabah}}\n|-\n| 3\n| [[Abdullah Sani Abdul Hamid]]\n| [[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|People's Justice Party]] ([[Pakatan Harapan]])\n| {{pseat|Kapar}}\n| {{flag|Selangor}}\n|-\n| 4\n| [[Ahmad Faizal Azumu]]\n| [[Malaysian United Indigenous Party]] ([[Pakatan Harapan]])\n| {{pseat|Tambun}}\n| {{flag|Perak}}\n|-\n| 5\n| [[Ahmad Hassan (Malaysian politician)|Ahmad Hassan]]\n| [[Sabah Heritage Party]]\n| {{pseat|Papar}}\n| {{flag|Sabah}}\n|-\n| 6\n| [[Akmal Nasrullah Mohd Nasir|Akmal Nasrullah Nasir]]\n| [[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|People's Justice Party]] ([[Pakatan Harapan]])\n| {{pseat|Johor Bahru}}\n| {{flag|Johor}}\n|-\n| 7\n| [[Ali Biju]]\n| [[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|People's Justice Party]] ([[Pakatan Harapan]])\n| {{pseat|Saratok}}\n| {{flag|Sarawak}}\n|-\n| 8\n| [[Alice Lau (politician)|Alice Lau Kiong Yieng]]\n| [[Democratic Action Party]] ([[Pakatan Harapan]])\n