text-align:center;\"| '''Absent (16)'''<ref name=\"absent and did not participate\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2019/04/12/maszlee-three-other-pakatan-mps-among-those-absent-from-article-12-vote/|title=Maszlee, three other Pakatan MPs among those absent during Article 1(2) vote|author1=Mazwin Nik Anis|author2=Joseph Kaos Jr|work=The Star|date=12 April 2019|accessdate=15 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190415033523/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2019/04/12/maszlee-three-other-pakatan-mps-among-those-absent-from-article-12-vote/|archive-date=15 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"undetermined\">{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/04/12/law-minister-maszlee-among-four-pakatan-mps-absent-from-constitution-amendm/1742629|title=Law minister: Maszlee among four Pakatan MPs absent from Constitution amendment vote|author=Emmanuel Santa Maria Chin|publisher=The Malay Mail|date=12 April 2019|accessdate=15 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190415032900/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/04/12/law-minister-maszlee-among-four-pakatan-mps-absent-from-constitution-amendm/1742629|archivedate=15 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1\n| [[Abdul Hadi Awang]]\n| [[Pan-Malaysian Islamic Party]] ([[Gagasan Sejahtera]])\n| {{pseat|Marang}}\n| {{flag|Terengganu}}\n|-\n| 2\n| [[Abdul Rahman Mohamad]]\n| [[United Malays National Organisation]] ([[Barisan Nasional]])\n| {{pseat|Lipis}}\n| {{flag|Pahang}}\n|-\n| 3\n| [[Abu Hussin Hafiz Syed]]\n| [[Independent (politician)|Independent]]\n| {{pseat|Bukit Gantang}}\n| {{flag|Perak}}\n|-\n| 4\n| [[Ahmad Nazlan Idris]]\n| [[United Malays National Organisation]] ([[Barisan Nasional]])\n| {{pseat|Jerantut}}\n| {{flag|Pahang}}\n|-\n| 5\n| [[Ahmad Zahid Hamidi]]\n| [[United Malays National Organisation]] ([[Barisan Nasional]])\n| {{pseat|Bagan Datok}}\n| {{flag|Perak}}\n|-\n| 6\n| [[Azalina Othman Said]]\n| [[United Malays National Organisation]] ([[Barisan Nasional]])\n| {{pseat|Pengerang}}\n| {{flag|Johor}}\n|-\n| 7\n| [[Idris Jusoh]]\n| [[United Malays National Organisation]] ([[Barisan Nasional]])\n| {{pseat|Besut}}\n| {{flag|Terengganu}}\n|-\n| 8\n| [[Ismail Mohamed Said]]\n| [[United Malays National Organisation]] ([[Barisan Nasional]])\n| {{pseat|Kuala Krau}}\n| {{flag|Pahang}}\n|-\n| 9\n| [[Khairy Jamaluddin]]\n| [[United Malays National Organisation]] ([[Barisan Nasional]])\n| {{pseat|Rembau}}\n| {{flag|Negeri Sembilan}}\n|-\n| 10\n| [[Maszlee Malik]]\n| [[Malaysian United Indigenous Party]] ([[Pakatan Harapan]])\n| {{pseat|Simpang Renggam}}\n| {{flag|Johor}}\n|-\n| 11\n| [[Muslimin Yahaya]]\n| [[Malaysian United Indigenous Party]] ([[Pakatan Harapan]])\n| {{pseat|Sungai Besar}}\n| {{flag|Selangor}}\n|-\n| 12\n| [[Najib Razak]]\n| [[United Malays National Organisation]] ([[Barisan Nasional]])\n| {{pseat|Pekan}}\n| {{flag|Pahang}}\n|-\n| 13\n| [[Mohamed Nazri Abdul Aziz|Nazri Aziz]]\n| [[United Malays National Organisation]] ([[Barisan Nasional]])\n| {{pseat|Padang Rengas}}\n| {{flag|Perak}}\n|-\n| 14\n| [[Noor Amin Ahmad]]\n| [[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|People's Justice Party]] ([[Pakatan Harapan]])\n| {{pseat|Kangar}}\n| {{flag|Perlis}}\n|-\n| 15\n| [[Shamsul Iskandar Md. Akin|Shamsul Iskandar]]\n| [[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|People's Justice Party]] ([[Pakatan Harapan]])\n| {{pseat|Hang Tuah Jaya}}\n| {{flag|Malacca}}\n|-\n| 16\n| [[Yamani Hafez Musa]]\n| [[United Malays National Organisation]] ([[Barisan Nasional]])\n| {{pseat|Sipitang}}\n| {{flag|Sabah}}\n|- bgcolor=\"#A4A2A2\"\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{white|'''Vacant (1)'''}}\n|-\n| 1\n| colspan=\"2\"| ''Vacant''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theedgemarkets.com/article/sandakan-mp-stephen-wong-passes-away|title=Sandakan MP Stephen Wong passes away|work=Bernama|publisher=The Edge Markets|date=28 March 2019|accessdate=15 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190415084258/https://www.theedgemarkets.com/article/sandakan-mp-stephen-wong-passes-away|archivedate=15 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| {{pseat|Sandakan}}\n| {{flag|Sabah}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"5\"| ''Source: [https://drive.google.com/file/d/1ETHeh0mRBhX0qVSqT2jUmHjnngb9dyp_/view Division result] from an unspecified article on [[Malaysiakini]] via [https://www.reddit.com/r/malaysia/comments/bcl2ch/list_of_mps_who_voted_for_the_amendment_of/ Reddit]''\n|}\n\nA separate motion by [[Santubong (federal constituency)|Santubong]] MP, [[Wan Junaidi Tuanku Jaafar]], for the bill to be submitted to a special committee of Parliament for a review was supported by only 60 MPs and opposed by 136 MPs. The full sitting of parliament was one MP short as [[Wong Tien Fatt#Death|Wong Tien Fatt]] had died from a heart attack a week prior to the vote.<ref name=\"no two-thirds majority\"/><ref name=\"Sabah Sarawak status stays following amendment failure\"/> As the bill had failed to reach the required two-thirds majority, it would not get a third reading in Parliament. Despite this, PKR President Anwar Ibrahim said that he was satisfied with the show of support from government MPs and their coalition allies.<ref name=\"UMNO/BN abstained in the voting process\"/> Prime Minister Mahathir said that, despite the failure of the bill to pass, he did not expect future efforts at amending the constitution to fail. He also stated that, in response to a request by [[Pontian (federal constituency)|Pontian]] MP [[Ahmad Maslan]], there was no need to refer the amendment to the [[Conference of Rulers]] for review as it was not within their remit, but there would be no opposition from the government if members of parliament sought the formation of a select committee to review the 1963 agreement.<ref name=\"six hours debate\"/><ref name=\"Sabah Sarawak status stays following amendment failure\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/04/09/dr-m-no-need-to-refer-federal-constitution-amendment-for-sarawak-sabah-to-r/1741507|title=Dr M: No need to refer Federal Constitution amendment for Sarawak, Sabah to Rulers' Conference|author=Yiswaree Palansamy|publisher=The Malay Mail|date=9 April 2019|accessdate=9 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190410044250/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/04/09/dr-m-no-need-to-refer-federal-constitution-amendment-for-sarawak-sabah-to-r/1741507|archivedate=10 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Domestic response ==\nFollowing the commitment shown by Prime Minister Mahathir, and responding to the need for review, Sabah Social Activist Patrick Sindu suggested that the steering committee set up to review the 1963 agreement should also invite the [[Government of the United Kingdom|British government]] for feedback considering they were party to the original agreement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news.cfm?NewsID=127917|title=Invite British govt to give views|work=Bernama|publisher=Daily Express|date=13 October 2018|accessdate=4 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404113842/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news.cfm?NewsID=127917|archivedate=4 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Sarawak Assistant Minister of Law, State-Federal Relations and Project Monitoring [[:ms:Sharifah Hasidah Sayeed Aman Ghazali|Sharifah Hasidah Sayeed Aman Ghazali]] pointed out that any review of the 1963 agreement should be aimed at remedying any violation of the terms, spirit and intent of the formation of the Federation of Malaysia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2018/11/07/review-of-ma63-should-focus-on-breach-of-terms-of-formation-of-malaysia/|title=Review of MA63 should focus on breach of terms of formation of Malaysia|publisher=The Borneo Post|date=7 November 2018|accessdate=4 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404083346/https://www.theborneopost.com/2018/11/07/review-of-ma63-should-focus-on-breach-of-terms-of-formation-of-malaysia/|archivedate=4 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Both the Sabah Council of Churches (SCC) and the Association of Churches in Sarawak (ACS) have called for a full restoration of religious freedom.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/03/14/as-ma63-review-begins-sabah-churches-call-for-complete-religious-freedom/1732617|title=As MA63 review begins, Sabah churches call for complete religious freedom|author=Julia Chan|publisher=The Malay Mail|date=14 March 2019|accessdate=6 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406005616/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/03/14/as-ma63-review-begins-sabah-churches-call-for-complete-religious-freedom/1732617|archivedate=6 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2019/03/27/acs-calls-for-freedom-of-religion-to-be-restored-in-accordance-with-ma63-constitution/|title=ACS calls for freedom of religion to be restored in accordance with MA63, Constitution|author=Sharon Ling|work=The Star|date=27 March 2019|accessdate=6 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406010227/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2019/03/27/acs-calls-for-freedom-of-religion-to-be-restored-in-accordance-with-ma63-constitution/|archive-date=6 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://barnabasfund.org/en/news/sabah-churches-press-for-religious-freedom-as-malaysia-debates-giving-more-power-to-region|title=Sabah churches press for religious freedom as Malaysia debates giving more power to region|publisher=Barnabas Fund|date=3 April 2019|accessdate=6 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406043341/https://barnabasfund.org/en/news/sabah-churches-press-for-religious-freedom-as-malaysia-debates-giving-more-power-to-region|archivedate=6 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe President of the Sabah Law Society Brenndon Keith Soh issued a statement saying that legal action could be taken against the federal government if it fails to fully implement the 1963 agreement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/03/12/legal-action-as-last-resort-if-fed-govt-fails-to-fully-implement-ma63/|title=Legal action as last resort if fed govt fails to fully implement MA63|author=Neil Brian Joseph|publisher=The Borneo Post|date=12 March 2019|accessdate=4 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404110625/https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/03/12/legal-action-as-last-resort-if-fed-govt-fails-to-fully-implement-ma63/|archivedate=4 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2019/03/13/sabah-sarawak-can-sue-putrajaya-if-ma63-not-implemented/|title=Sabah, Sarawak can sue Putrajaya if MA63 not implemented|author=Tracy Patrick|publisher=Free Malaysia Today|date=13 March 2019|accessdate=6 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406011539/https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2019/03/13/sabah-sarawak-can-sue-putrajaya-if-ma63-not-implemented/|archivedate=6 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Arnold Puyok, a commenter on Sabah and Sarawak affairs, stressed that the restoration of the territorial status of Sabah and Sarawak should be viewed from a perspective that encompasses Malaysian [[federalism]], and not with a bias towards either Sabah or Sarawak.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/what-you-think/2019/04/04/ma63-equal-partnership-and-the-future-of-the-malaysian-federation-arnold-pu/1739937|title=MA63, 'equal partnership' and the future of the Malaysian federation|author=Arnold Puyok|publisher=The Malay Mail|date=4 April 2019|accessdate=4 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404151040/https://www.malaymail.com/news/what-you-think/2019/04/04/ma63-equal-partnership-and-the-future-of-the-malaysian-federation-arnold-pu/1739937|archivedate=4 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Sabah Sarawak Rights-Australia New Zealand Incorporation (SSRANZ) President Robert Pei pointed to parallels between the issues surrounding the 1963 agreement and those that arose during the decolonisation of [[Mauritius]] in 1968 when the island nation [[Chagos Archipelago sovereignty dispute|challenged the validity]] of the 1965 Agreement with the [[United Kingdom]] removing the [[Chagos Archipelago]] from Mauritian control. According to Pei, the 1963 agreement was invalid from inception as, per a judgement by the International Court of Justice (ICJ), Sabah and Sarawak were both still British colonies, and not sovereign nations, at the time and thus had no power to sign treaties.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/04/02/activist-cites-1965-mauritius-agreement-as-basis-for-ma63-issue/|title=Activist cites 1965 Mauritius 'agreement' as basis for MA63 issue|publisher=The Borneo Post|date=2 April 2019|accessdate=4 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404112245/https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/04/02/activist-cites-1965-mauritius-agreement-as-basis-for-ma63-issue/|archivedate=4 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Malaysian Chinese Association]] (MCA) Sabah Women Chief Pamela Yong said that she doubted the \"sincerity\" of the federal government and perceived it as a move to temporarily placate discontented residents of the two states.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2019/03/16/mca-questions-sincerity-behind-move-to-amend-article-1-2/|title=MCA questions sincerity behind move to amend Article 1 (2)|author=Tracy Patrick|publisher=Free Malaysia Today|date=16 March 2019|accessdate=7 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190407025516/https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2019/03/16/mca-questions-sincerity-behind-move-to-amend-article-1-2/|archivedate=7 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[State Reform Party]] (STAR Sarawak) President Lina Soo,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/03/11/dont-rush-into-amending-federal-constitution-on-sarawak-rights-party-chief/1731467|title=Don't rush into amending Federal Constitution on Sarawak rights, party chief tells MPs|author=Sulok Tawie|publisher=The Malay Mail|date=11 March 2019|accessdate=4 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404130004/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/03/11/dont-rush-into-amending-federal-constitution-on-sarawak-rights-party-chief/1731467|archivedate=4 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Homeland Solidarity Party]] (STAR Sabah) President, and MP, [[Jeffrey Kitingan]] as well as [[Nancy Shukri]] of the [[Parti Pesaka Bumiputera Bersatu|United Bumiputera Heritage Party]] (PBB) of Sarawak all issued statements cautioning against rushing the bill and have strongly emphasised the need for a complete review. Dr Kitingan expressed concerns that the amendment was \"shrouded in secrecy\", while MP Nancy Shukri is one of many voices urging the government to release a draft to them.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2019/03/31/show-us-draft-ma63-bill-say-nancy-shukri/|title=Show us draft MA63 bill, says Nancy Shukri|author=Larissa Lumadan|publisher=Free Malaysia Today|date=31 March 2019|accessdate=4 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404125614/https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2019/03/31/show-us-draft-ma63-bill-say-nancy-shukri/|archivedate=4 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.borneotoday.net/defer-tabling-article-12-and-await-other-amendments-dr-jeffrey/|title=Defer Tabling Article 1 (2) and Await Other Amendments - Dr. Jeffrey|publisher=Borneo Today|date=31 March 2019|accessdate=4 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404125025/https://www.borneotoday.net/defer-tabling-article-12-and-await-other-amendments-dr-jeffrey/|archivedate=4 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \nThe Sarawak committee that is acting as consultants on the negotiations have stated they will refrain from commenting until they have been provided with the contents of the bill.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.themalaysianinsight.com/s/143804|title=We'll comment on Sarawak, Sabah status bill when we see it, says Sarawak MA63 panel|author=Desmond Davidson|publisher=The Malaysian Insight|date=28 March 2019|accessdate=4 April 2019|url-access=subscription|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404163209/https://www.themalaysianinsight.com/s/143804|archive-date=4 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nChief Minister of Sabah, Shafie Apdal, said that once the amendment was passed, Sabah would consider dropping the word \"state\" from official documents,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/03/17/cm-sabah-mulling-dropping-term-state/1733675|title=CM: Sabah mulling dropping term 'state'|publisher=The Malay Mail|date=17 March 2019|accessdate=6 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406015317/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/03/17/cm-sabah-mulling-dropping-term-state/1733675|archivedate=6 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> where as Chief Minister of Sarawak, [[Abang Abdul Rahman Zohari]], said that the word \"state\" would be dropped completely.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2019/03/469790/sarawak-drop-word-state|title=Sarawak to drop the word 'state'|author=Goh Pei Pei|publisher=New Straits Times|date=16 March 2019|accessdate=6 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406015856/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2019/03/469790/sarawak-drop-word-state|archive-date=6 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Former Sabah [[Pan-Malaysian Islamic Party]] (PAS) Deputy Commissioner, and lawyer, Hamid Ismail responded to these statements by claiming that such actions would violate the 1963 agreement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/03/19/dropping-state-violation-of-ma63-lawyer/|title=Dropping 'state' violation of MA63 \u2014 Lawyer|publisher=The Borneo Post|date=19 March 2019|accessdate=6 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406015527/https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/03/19/dropping-state-violation-of-ma63-lawyer/|archivedate=6 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> [[United Sabah Party]] (PBS) Youth Chief Christopher Mandut countered this claim, instead arguing that the use of the word \"state\" was an inexact translation of \"negeri\" as used in the modern political sense. He cited [[Germany]] and [[Italy]] as examples of states that were not \"negeri\" but were nonetheless referred to as \"states\" in the sovereign sense.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2019/03/23/pas-man-doesnt-know-what-state-means-in-ma63-says-pbs/|title=PAS man doesn't know what 'state' means in MA63, says PBS|author=Tracy Patrick|publisher=Free Malaysia Today|date=23 March 2019|accessdate=6 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406015633/https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2019/03/23/pas-man-doesnt-know-what-state-means-in-ma63-says-pbs/|archivedate=6 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> STAR Sarawak President Lina Soo also issued a statement to this effect, saying that \"Borneo States\" differs from \"states of Malaya\" (\"negeri\"), which specifically referred to constituent territories of a sovereign nation. She claimed that the British used \"state\", when renaming the \"[[British Borneo]] Territories\" to \"Borneo States of Sabah and Sarawak\", to refer to \"self-governing entities with a history, laws, political and social systems\".<ref name=\"called for deep review\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/04/09/soo-stop-the-drama-over-article-12-amendment-bill/|title=Soo: Stop the drama over Article 1(2) amendment Bill|publisher=The Borneo Post|date=9 April 2019|accessdate=9 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190409070856/https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/04/09/soo-stop-the-drama-over-article-12-amendment-bill/|archivedate=9 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOpposition leader [[Ismail Sabri Yaakob]] expressed the opposition's support for the bill, but he also had concerns over various aspects of its content, such as the absence of any reference to the 1963 agreement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2019/04/477844/ismail-why-no-mention-ma63-amendment-bill|title=Ismail: Why no mention of MA63 in amendment bill?|author=Syed Umar Ariff|publisher=New Straits Times|date=9 April 2019|accessdate=10 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190410140040/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2019/04/477844/ismail-why-no-mention-ma63-amendment-bill|archive-date=10 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He also expressed concerns that the bill was being rushed through without a careful review by the Parliamentary Select Committee.<ref name=\"six hours debate\"/>\n\n=== Reactions after the amendment bill tabling on 4 April ===\nIn an interview, Nancy Shukri, the PBB MP representing [[Batang Sadong (federal constituency)|Batang Sadong]], perceived the proposed amendment as a \"trap\" as she could not see how the hastily proposed amendment could restore the position of Sabah and Sarawak. She also noted the absence of several Sarawak PH MPs when the bill was tabled during its first reading on 4 April and added stated her desire for a deferral of the amendment to a select committee for an in-depth review,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2019/04/05/constitutional-amendment-a-trap-says-sarawak-mp/|title=Constitutional amendment a 'trap', says Sarawak MP|author=Larissa Lumadan|publisher=Free Malaysia Today|date=5 April 2019|accessdate=5 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190405091312/https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2019/04/05/constitutional-amendment-a-trap-says-sarawak-mp/|archivedate=5 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> with an eye towards ensuring related legislation is also amended accordingly. Nonetheless, she called for members of Gabungan Parti Sarawak (GPS) and Pakatan Harapan (PH) to come together in a show of bipartisanship and to cooperate in ensuring the status of Sarawak is restored.<ref name=\"six hours debate\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/04/08/prioritise-sarawak-in-second-reading/|title=Prioritise Sarawak in second reading|author=Joash Kong|publisher=The Borneo Post|date=8 April 2019|accessdate=8 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190408050820/https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/04/08/prioritise-sarawak-in-second-reading/|archivedate=8 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> STAR Sarawak President Lina Soo also announced her support for a temporary withdrawal of the bill and to debate it in the Sarawak legislative assembly as well as seek the affirmation of the people. She stated her concern that \"Without the safeguards and assurances defined in the explanatory statement, this Bill is a manipulative and repugnant act which is like giving a blank cheque to PH to write, or akin to locking ourselves in a prison and throwing the keys away\".<ref name=\"called for deep review\"/>\n\nA Sarawakian lawyer, [[:ms:Robert Lau Hui Yew|Robert Lau Hui Yew]] from SUPP,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/politics/2018/05/364853/supp-man-robert-lau-appointed-senator|title=SUPP man Robert Lau appointed as senator|author=Mohd Roji Kawi|publisher=New Straits Times|date=3 May 2018|accessdate=14 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180503131946/https://www.nst.com.my/news/politics/2018/05/364853/supp-man-robert-lau-appointed-senator |archivedate=3 May 2018}}</ref> dismissed the proposed amendment as \"just playing with the construction of a sentence\". According to his analysis, the amendment merely splits the 1976 agreement into two parts, but is effectively the same sentence. He further alleges that the drafting of the amendment could have been a simple process and yet \"the drafters are trying to confuse and hold on to the assimilated nature of Malaya in the guise of Malaysia\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2019/04/05/lawyer-proposed-amendment-to-honour-ma63-just-playing-with-sentence-construction/|title=Lawyer: Proposed amendment to honour MA63 'just playing with sentence construction'|author=Andy Chua|work=The Star|date=5 April 2019|accessdate=5 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406160941/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2019/04/05/lawyer-proposed-amendment-to-honour-ma63-just-playing-with-sentence-construction/|archive-date=6 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Similar views were also expressed by former Sabah Chief Minister, and [[Sabah Progressive Party]] (SAPP) President, [[Yong Teck Lee]] together with SUPP Youth Chief Michael Tiang and Sarawak MP [[Tiong King Sing]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2019/04/05/former-sabah-cm-says-proposed-constitutional-amendment-hollow/|title=Former Sabah CM says proposed Constitutional amendment hollow and meaningless|author=Muguntan Vanar|work=The Star|date=5 April 2019|accessdate=6 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406023857/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2019/04/05/former-sabah-cm-says-proposed-constitutional-amendment-hollow/|archive-date=6 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/04/06/proposed-amendment-to-article-12-an-insult-yong/|title=Proposed amendment to Article 1(2) an insult \u2013 Yong|publisher=The Borneo Post|date=6 April 2019|accessdate=6 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406023606/https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/04/06/proposed-amendment-to-article-12-an-insult-yong/|archivedate=6 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/04/05/no-reason-for-sarawak-mps-to-vote-for-amendment-bill-tiang/|title=No reason for Sarawak MPs to vote for amendment Bill \u2013 Tiang|author=Lim How Pim|publisher=The Borneo Post|date=5 April 2019|accessdate=6 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406013700/https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/04/05/no-reason-for-sarawak-mps-to-vote-for-amendment-bill-tiang/|archivedate=6 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/04/07/amendment-bill-not-reflecting-spirit-of-ma63-mp/|title=Amendment Bill not reflecting spirit of MA63 \u2014 MP|publisher=The Borneo Post|date=7 April 2019|accessdate=7 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190407053823/https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/04/07/amendment-bill-not-reflecting-spirit-of-ma63-mp/|archivedate=7 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nSarawak Legal Counsel JC Fong further said that the federal government should redefine the \"federation term\" to achieve equal status for both entities as through the bill reading, there will still be 13 states in Malaysia including Sarawak and Sabah based on Clause (2) in the bill.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/04/04/redefine-federation-for-sarawak-sabah-to-achieve-equal-status-says-lawyer/1739979|title=Redefine 'Federation' for Sarawak, Sabah to achieve equal status, says lawyer|author=Raynore Mering|publisher=The Malay Mail|date=4 April 2019|accessdate=5 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190405095031/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/04/04/redefine-federation-for-sarawak-sabah-to-achieve-equal-status-says-lawyer/1739979|archivedate=5 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> PBS President [[Maximus Ongkili]] described the proposed amendment as a \"disappointment\" as there is really nothing in it when Sabah continued to be mentioned as one of the 13 states through the tabling on 4 April when the actual reason for the amendment is to restore the position of the two entities as equal partners, adding that is why most of the opposition MPs from both entities proposing a review by a select committee for a study and modification on the bill which then will be referred to the two current state assemblies for debate and adoption before the national Parliament being allowed to make a vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2019/04/05/pbs-says-will-not-support-proposed-article-1-2-amendment/|title=PBS says will not support proposed Article 1(2) amendment in its present form|work=The Star|date=5 April 2019|accessdate=5 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406150906/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2019/04/05/pbs-says-will-not-support-proposed-article-1-2-amendment/|archive-date=6 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Another Sabah MP [[Anifah Aman]] urge the federal government not to be hasty with a deep study are required before its tabling as the issue has long been a thorny issue and a cause of growing unhappiness amongst Sabahans and Sarawakians residents.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2019/04/04/anifah-wants-sabah-sarawak-legislative-assemblies-to-approve-proposed-constitutional-amendments/|title=Anifah wants Sabah, Sarawak legislative assemblies to approve proposed constitutional amendments|author=Muguntan Vanar|work=The Star|date=4 April 2019|accessdate=4 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404132117/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2019/04/04/anifah-wants-sabah-sarawak-legislative-assemblies-to-approve-proposed-constitutional-amendments/|archive-date=4 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Universiti Malaysia Sabah]] (UMS) political analyst Lee Kuok Tiung calling the amendment as \"nonsensical\", saying that with such definition during the tabling, he wondering how the two entities can be equal partners.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.themalaysianinsight.com/s/145967|title=Putrajaya at odds with Sabah, Sarawak over equal status bill's wording|author=Jason Santos|publisher=The Malaysian Insight|date=7 April 2019|accessdate=7 April 2019|url-access=subscription|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190407033338/https://www.themalaysianinsight.com/s/145967|archive-date=7 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Former Minister in the Prime Minister Department and [[Parti Bersatu Rakyat Sabah|United Sabah People's Party]] (PBRS) President [[Joseph Kurup]] said the bill is far from what the people in the two entities wished but urging the matter should not being prolonged as it will causing further tense relationship between the two entities with the federation.<ref name=\"second reading\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/133516/bill-needs-approval-of-sabah-sarawak-assemblies-kurup/|title=Bill needs approval of Sabah, Sarawak assemblies: Kurup|author=Johan Aziz|publisher=Daily Express|date=7 April 2019|accessdate=7 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190407080553/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/133516/bill-needs-approval-of-sabah-sarawak-assemblies-kurup/|archivedate=7 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> As a solution, Kurup calling Minister Liew to postponed the tabling and held discussion with all of the involved MPs before presenting the bill again in the Parliament for its second reading and debate.<ref name=\"second reading\"/> The Vice President of [[Liberal Democratic Party (Malaysia)|Liberal Democratic Party]] (LDP) Yew Chau Khiong said the amendment bill is too \"hasty\" in its first reading, calling the governments of the two entities together with the Advocates Association of Sarawak (AAS) and Sabah Law Society to make a more in-depth study followed by a discussion on the proposed amendment before being referred to a select committee in Parliament prior to debate and voting as an hasty amendment which just passed for the sake of achieving an objective will only resulting in consequences that affecting the lives of future generations as evidenced in the current situation of both entities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/04/08/amendment-bill-too-hasty-on-first-reading-ldp/|title=Amendment bill too hasty on first reading \u2013 LDP|publisher=The Borneo Post|date=8 April 2019|accessdate=8 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190408151202/https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/04/08/amendment-bill-too-hasty-on-first-reading-ldp/|archivedate=8 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the claim made by Minister Liew who said the two Chief Ministers have been consulted over the bill, Sarawak Chief Minister Abang Zohari made a clear statement that no approval was given by both Chief Ministers from Sabah and Sarawak on the amendment in its current form with the cabinet committee appointed for the review of the 1963 agreement never discussed the actual wording of the amendment in its meetings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/04/06/sabah-sarawak-cms-did-not-give-approval-on-amendment-of-article-12-says-aba/1740498|title=Sabah/Sarawak CMs did not give approval on amendment of Article 1(2), says Abang Johari|work=Bernama|publisher=The Malay Mail|date=6 April 2019|accessdate=6 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406124252/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/04/06/sabah-sarawak-cms-did-not-give-approval-on-amendment-of-article-12-says-aba/1740498|archivedate=6 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Abang Zohari further explained that they will support any amendment to the Federal Constitution or any law that seeks to restore their rights as according to the 1963 agreement but the amendments must not merely in form but of substantive nature.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/133555/abang-johari-explains-why-gps-not-supporting/|title=Abang Johari explains why GPS not supporting|work=Bernama|publisher=Daily Express|date=8 April 2019|accessdate=8 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190408054421/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/133555/abang-johari-explains-why-gps-not-supporting/|archivedate=8 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> PBB also respond to the appeal made by [[Chong Chieng Jen]] of the DAP in Sarawak through its Information Chief Idris Buang who said the federal government need to respond to a list of claims made by the Sarawak government delegation in the committee reviewing the 1963 agreement which includes Sarawak's stand on non-negotiable matters pertaining to its rights over land, continental shelf, natural resources (oil and gas and mining rights) as well as the special grants and [[capitation (healthcare)|capitation]] grants along with the need for equal share of parliamentary seats following the [[Singapore in Malaysia|exit of Singapore]] from the federation in 1965 as the proposed amendment is just not simply to get it done to prevent getting a supposed rights restoration which is just \"beautiful in the outside, but actually empty inside\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/04/08/want-sarawaks-support-for-article-12-revision-answer-our-questions-first-sa/1740926|title=Want Sarawak's support for Article 1(2) revision? Answer our questions first, says PBB info chief|author=Sulok Tawie|publisher=The Malay Mail|date=8 April 2019|accessdate=8 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190408053315/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/04/08/want-sarawaks-support-for-article-12-revision-answer-our-questions-first-sa/1740926|archivedate=8 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Response by the federal government and other allied parties on the definition of the bill ===\nPrime Minister Mahathir said afterwards that it is up to Sabah and Sarawak MPs to support the bill, adding that what they have announced is that they will recognise the amendment as an agreement among three entities \u2014 the Federation of Malaya, Sabah and Sarawak. But as the previous constitution did not make it clear, they have to amend the constitution by getting two-thirds majority vote in the Parliament.<ref name=\"MA63 motion tabled\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theedgemarkets.com/article/ma63-motion-tabled|title=MA63 motion tabled|author1=Chester Tay|author2=Adam Aziz|publisher=The Edge Markets|date=5 April 2019|accessdate=5 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190405090508/https://www.theedgemarkets.com/article/ma63-motion-tabled|archivedate=5 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Minister Liew also said that both Sabah and Sarawak leaders have been consulted and have deliberated over the issue with both entities will be termed as territories, telling that if the opposition MPs want to establish a separate special select committee on the matter, it can be done but since it is a government bill, it will not initiate a proposal to establish one.<ref name=\"MA63 motion tabled\"/> During Mahathir visit to Sabah on 6 April, the Prime Minister assuring the public that the amendment is not merely a cosmetic with the federal government will fulfill its promise for the two entities to get equal status to Peninsular Malaysia, officially declaring that:\n\n{{quote|We promised we will recognise the signatures to the Malaysia 1963 agreement was by Sabah, Sarawak and Peninsular Malaysia. We will recognise these three regions as members of the federation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/04/06/dr-m-amendment-bill-to-article-1-2-to-recognise-sabah-and-sarawak-as-member/1740519|title=Dr M: Amendment Bill to Article 1 (2) to recognise Sabah and Sarawak as members of the federation|author=Julia Chan|publisher=The Malay Mail|date=6 April 2019|accessdate=6 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406132002/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/04/06/dr-m-amendment-bill-to-article-1-2-to-recognise-sabah-and-sarawak-as-member/1740519|archivedate=6 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.themalaysianinsight.com/s/145917|title=Putrajaya sincere in restoring rights of Sabah, Sarawak, says PM|publisher=The Malaysian Insight|date=6 April 2019|accessdate=7 April 2019|url-access=subscription|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190407030710/https://www.themalaysianinsight.com/s/145917|archive-date=7 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>|[[Mahathir Mohamad]], Prime Minister of Malaysia.}}\n\nResponding to the criticism towards him and the federal government on the bill content definition during the tabling, Minister Liew explained that through the 1963 agreement, every parties have agreed on the definition but it became null in 1966 following the Singapore exit from the federation in 1965 where an amendment was made in the year of the [[:wikt:nullification|nullification]].<ref name=\"amendment background\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bharian.com.my/berita/nasional/2019/04/549584/pindaan-perlembagaan-kembalikan-status-sabah-sarawak|title=Pindaan Perlembagaan kembalikan status Sabah, Sarawak|trans-title=Amendment of the Constitution restores Sabah, Sarawak status|author=Poliana Ronnie Sidom|language=Malay|publisher=Berita Harian|date=6 April 2019|accessdate=6 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406151147/https://www.bharian.com.my/berita/nasional/2019/04/549584/pindaan-perlembagaan-kembalikan-status-sabah-sarawak|archive-date=6 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"flashback of 1976 amendment\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/133515/liew-why-oppose-it-now-/|title=Liew: Why oppose it now?|author=Mardinah Jikur|publisher=Daily Express|date=7 April 2019|accessdate=7 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190407054026/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/133515/liew-why-oppose-it-now-/|archivedate=7 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 1976, another amendment was made to placed both Sabah and Sarawak as \"negeri\" by dropping the words like \"the States of Malaya, namely\" and \"the Borneo States, namely\" from the original definition of the States of the Federation of Malaysia where it receive two-thirds majority vote from the Parliament including the support from the MPs of the two entities itself thus saying the leaders from the two only realising their mistake recently when they who are supposed to oppose the previous 1976 amendment.<ref name=\"amendment background\"/><ref name=\"flashback of 1976 amendment\"/> The statement are similarly echoed by Sarawak PH Chairman Chong Chieng Jen who agreed that it is actually PBB and SUPP MPs who support the downgrade of Sarawak status to one of the 13 states in Malaysia when they were still part of the BN coalition without realising its implications today.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/politics/2019/03/467786/pbb-and-supp-supported-1976-constitutional-amendment-chong|title=PBB and SUPP supported 1976 constitutional amendment : Chong|work=Bernama|publisher=New Straits Times|date=10 March 2019|accessdate=6 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406160827/https://www.nst.com.my/news/politics/2019/03/467786/pbb-and-supp-supported-1976-constitutional-amendment-chong|archive-date=6 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 April, both the [[Democratic Action Party]] (DAP) branches in East Malaysia through Chong Chieng Jen for Sarawak and [[Chan Foong Hin]] for Sabah appeal to both opposition MPs in the two entities to stop playing politics and remove their egos as the bill will soon be debated and put to vote on 9 April,<ref name=\"reason for exclusion\">{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/04/07/gps-urged-to-support-amendment-bill-to-regain-sarawak-and-sabahs-rightful-s/1740740|title=We need your support to push Bill to restore equality for Sarawak, Pakatan tells GPS|author=Sulok Tawie|publisher=The Malay Mail|date=7 April 2019|accessdate=7 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190407153901/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/04/07/gps-urged-to-support-amendment-bill-to-regain-sarawak-and-sabahs-rightful-s/1740740|archivedate=7 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> adding that co-operation between government and opposition MPs are needed to undo the wrongdoings of the past as any failure to pass the bill in the end will only resulting to negative consequences on the negotiation for the rights in the 1963 agreement.<ref name=\"co-operation are necessary\">{{cite web|url=https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2019/04/07/sabah-dap-pleads-with-opposition-to-back-amendment-bill/|title=Sabah DAP pleads with opposition to back amendment bill|author=Durie Rainer Fong|publisher=Free Malaysia Today|date=7 April 2019|accessdate=7 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190407154024/https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2019/04/07/sabah-dap-pleads-with-opposition-to-back-amendment-bill/|archivedate=7 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Chan explained the amendment were indeed seeking to reverse the previous amendment in 1976 which placed both entities as one of 13 states in Malaysia as the 1963 agreement committee are still doing its work with more amendments to come soon.<ref name=\"co-operation are necessary\"/> On the reason behind the exclusion of several phrases as mentioned before, Chong stated that it was due to an earlier discussion made by the committee who feel both of the entities are not the only states on the island of Borneo as there are also the country of [[Brunei]] and Indonesian [[Kalimantan]] provinces, explaining that the proposed amendment is similar in structure to the original Article 4 (1) of the Federal Constitution even with the exclusion.<ref name=\"reason for exclusion\"/>\n\nSimilar view were also expressed earlier by Sarawak PKR lawmaker [[See Chee How]] who urging every MPs to put aside their political differences to fulfill the long-waited aspiration and hope of all Sarawakians and Sabahans to right the wrong of the last 43 years, adding that the committee and various working groups on the matters are still deliberating and working with steps are being taken to devolve the autonomous powers to both entities with their report is scheduled to be finalised and revealed by the committee in June.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/04/06/pkr-rep-put-aside-political-affiliations-to-support-amendment-bill-to-artic/1740518|title=PKR rep: Put aside political affiliations to support amendment Bill to Article 1 (2)|author=Sulok Tawie|publisher=The Malay Mail|date=6 April 2019|accessdate=7 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190407164552/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/04/06/pkr-rep-put-aside-political-affiliations-to-support-amendment-bill-to-artic/1740518|archivedate=7 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Sarawak Assemblyman from [[Padungan (state constituency)|Padungan]] Wong King Wei further said that opposition MPs should not doubt the present federal government sincerities to restore the rights of the two entities as if they were not care on the issues, they will just ignore by not doing anything like in the past over the matters.<ref name=\"without doubt\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/04/08/wong-why-so-much-negativity-over-proposed-amendment/|title=Wong: Why so much negativity over proposed amendment?|publisher=The Borneo Post|date=8 April 2019|accessdate=8 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190408034232/https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/04/08/wong-why-so-much-negativity-over-proposed-amendment/|archivedate=8 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He elaborated that several steps as the evidence of the federal government commitment have been shown such as the forming of a special committee on the 1963 agreement and even tabled an amendment bill to the Parliament, adding that the proposed amendment is just one of the first steps to restore the two entities rights as when their status have been restored, both entities can discuss further in the round table of the committee for further negotiations on their rights.<ref name=\"without doubt\"/>\n\nOther PKR MP from Sarawak such as [[Willie Mongin]] said the federal government move for the bill tabling is good as one of the first step to legally restore the two entities rights as according to the original 1963 agreement, but openly expressing that he is \"displeased\" with the words used in the proposed amendment and believed the wording could be refined, adding his proposals that \"Sarawak should be stated as Negara Sarawak (the Country of Sarawak) and Sabah as Negara Sabah (the Country of Sabah), not as one the states in the federation\" as the previous wording may indicate that both entities are just one of the states in the federation in par with Malay Peninsula states that will causing confusion and misinterpretation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/04/04/article-1-2-amendment-it-should-be-negara-sabah-sarawak-says-puncak-borneo-mp/|title=Article 1 (2) amendment: It should be 'Negara' Sabah & Sarawak, says Puncak Borneo MP|author=Rintos Mail|publisher=The Borneo Post|date=4 April 2019|accessdate=9 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190409030205/https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/04/04/article-1-2-amendment-it-should-be-negara-sabah-sarawak-says-puncak-borneo-mp/|archivedate=9 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[United Pasokmomogun Kadazandusun Murut Organisation]] (UPKO) also distancing their opinion differ than other government allied parties who simply supporting the bill, the party President [[Wilfred Madius Tangau]] agreed with the suggestion by opposition MPs to refer the amendment to the special committee before the second reading in Parliament on the evening of 9 April, stressing that the process must be fulfilled if the federal government was really serious in implementing the 1963 agreement and restoring their rights since a bill that was tabled in a rush will only drawn negative reactions from various parties in both of the entities as the amendment have implications that will subsequently transformed the federation governance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2019/04/08/madius-tangau-refer-amendment-on-bill-to-ma63-special-committee/|title=Madius Tangau: Refer amendment on Bill to MA63 special committee|author=Stephanie Lee|work=The Star|date=8 April 2019|accessdate=9 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190409002804/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2019/04/08/madius-tangau-refer-amendment-on-bill-to-ma63-special-committee/|archive-date=9 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Ronald Kiandee]] of the [[Malaysian United Indigenous Party]] (PPBM) said the bill must be approved by the MPs from both entities as it had long been anticipated to lift the ranks of the current two states.<ref name=\"six hours debate\"/>\n\n=== Aftermath of the bill second reading and subsequent voting ===\nPrime Minister Mahathir Mohamad said he did not expect the federal government bid to amend the constitution will fail, explaining that even with the unsatisfied result, they need to respect the decision made by opposition as every lawmaker has the right to vote \"whatever they have set their sights on\" and stressing the bill was not done in haste.<ref name=\"Sabah Sarawak status stays following amendment failure\"/> Deputy Prime Minister [[Wan Azizah Wan Ismail]] also expressed her deep disappointment over the result since she put a deep hope for the return of both entities status, adding that she thought when seeing the debate session everyone seemed to have agreed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bharian.com.my/berita/nasional/2019/04/551168/tpm-kecewa-pindaan-perlembagaan-gagal|title=TPM kecewa pindaan Perlembagaan gagal|trans-title=DPM disappointed amendment of the Constitution failed|author=Suhaila Shahrul Annuar|language=Malay|publisher=Berita Harian|date=10 April 2019|accessdate=10 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190410071658/https://www.bharian.com.my/berita/nasional/2019/04/551168/tpm-kecewa-pindaan-perlembagaan-gagal|archive-date=10 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> PKR President Anwar Ibrahim blamed the failure on the passage of the bill for the constitutional amendment to both UMNO and BN who are majority seen jointly choose to be \"abstained\" without giving their concrete reason in the voting, citing that since their long period of administrating the country, they did not even want to review the amendment of the country.<ref name=\"UMNO/BN abstained in the voting process\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/04/10/bn-mps-reason-why-bill-failed-says-anwar/1741546|title=BN MPs reason why Bill failed, says Anwar|work=Bernama|publisher=The Malay Mail|date=10 April 2019|accessdate=10 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190410074852/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/04/10/bn-mps-reason-why-bill-failed-says-anwar/1741546|archivedate=10 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He further added that the amendment was very meaningful and historic to the people of the country, especially to Sabah and Sarawak since the matter has been debated for a long time and we have heard the complaints of frustration and sadness of the people from both of the entities, adding that he could not understand why some people still disputed the matter when the old administration could not even moved an inch when they were in power for more than half a century.<ref name=\"six hours debate\"/> Sabah Chief Minister Shafie Apdal expressed his very deep disappointment on the failure to amend the constitution. In a statement, he expressed:\n\n{{quote|You can imagine, in particular, fundamental things that we cannot agree on and vote for it, what more other things that we can realise. It's already 55 years, we have waited for such a long time ... we are not saying that we should be in a hurry but, for God's sake, this is 55 years, this is a fundamental thing.<ref name=\"failure of passage forever remembered in history\"/>|[[Shafie Apdal]], Chief Minister of Sabah.}}\n\nDespite the deep disappointment, Shafie said the result of the voting is not the end of their struggle for equalities but instead its just becoming the first one after 55 years with the struggle will continues by all means, adding that he refuse to blaming anyone on the result when asked by the media whether he thought their counterpart Sarawak was to be blame for placing their politics above the bill with the Sabah government would continue their co-operation together with Sarawak government for the return of their rights.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/04/10/missed-opportunity-but-not-the-end-of-the-road-says-shafie-of-failed-bill/1741766|title=Missed opportunity but not the end of the road, says Shafie of failed Bill|author=Julia Chan|publisher=The Malay Mail|date=10 April 2019|accessdate=11 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190411083346/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/04/10/missed-opportunity-but-not-the-end-of-the-road-says-shafie-of-failed-bill/1741766|archivedate=11 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/04/11/sabah-to-continue-cooperation-with-sarawak-shafie-apdal/|title=Sabah to continue cooperation with Sarawak \u2014 Shafie Apdal|work=Bernama|publisher=The Borneo Post|date=11 April 2019|accessdate=12 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190412032505/https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/04/11/sabah-to-continue-cooperation-with-sarawak-shafie-apdal/|archivedate=12 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Former Chief Minister of Sabah and MP of UPKO, [[Bernard Giluk Dompok]] opined that all lawmakers should support the bill because the federal government had done what it was supposed to do to return the two entities status as before the 1976 amendment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/04/11/all-lawmakers-should-have-backed-ma63-bill-dompok/|title=All lawmakers should have backed MA63 Bill \u2013 Dompok|publisher=The Borneo Post|date=11 April 2019|accessdate=11 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190411024215/https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/04/11/all-lawmakers-should-have-backed-ma63-bill-dompok/|archivedate=11 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Petaling Jaya (federal constituency)|Petaling Jaya]] MP and social activist [[Maria Chin Abdullah]] called the 59 MPs who choose to abstained from the voting have shown through their own action that they are really not committed to the country reform agenda where they were blinded by their own political interests and have forsaken the struggles and aspirations of the people in the two entities which as a direct result of their conducts, these MPs have effectively retained both Sabah and Sarawak as only [[States and federal territories of Malaysia|states]] in the federation of Malaysia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.themalaysianinsight.com/s/146926|title=59 MPs have forsaken people of Sabah, Sarawak, says Maria Chin|publisher=The Malaysian Insight|date=10 April 2019|accessdate=11 April 2019|url-access=subscription|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190411073318/https://www.themalaysianinsight.com/s/146926|archive-date=11 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Minister of International Trade and Industry (Malaysia)|Minister of International Trade and Industry]] and President of the [[Sabah Heritage Party]] (WARISAN) [[Darell Leiking]] said the majority decision taken by opposition MPs evidently showing they have no dignity towards their voters, adding that it was a historical moment for the country when the Prime Minister have willing to read out the rationale behind amending the constitution which would have reinstated our status to the pre-1976 amendment, but instead all of these efforts been wasted by the opposition MPs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2019/04/10/no-dignity-in-abstaining-mps-told-on-amendment-bill/|title=No dignity in abstaining, MPs told on amendment bill|author=Durie Rainer Fong|publisher=Free Malaysia Today|date=10 April 2019|accessdate=10 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190410082733/https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2019/04/10/no-dignity-in-abstaining-mps-told-on-amendment-bill/|archivedate=10 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The PH coalition in Sarawak through their Secretary Senator, [[Alan Ling]] expressed their great disappointment as the historical opportunity to restore both entities status had been dashed to the ground by the decision of the opposition to abstained from voting, adding that the opposition especially GPS had intentionally failing the aspirations of Sarawakians which is totally unacceptable and beyond any justification with any further excuses given by GPS MPs have no merit as the wording on the proposed amendment have been agreed to be redefined as in the original version of 1963 agreement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/04/10/opportunity-to-restore-swak-sabahs-status-dashed-to-the-ground-by-gps-says-ling/|title=Opportunity to restore S'wak, Sabah's status 'dashed to the ground' by GPS, says Ling|author=Philip Kiew|publisher=The Borneo Post|date=10 April 2019|accessdate=10 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190410070806/https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/04/10/ling-opportunity-to-restore-swak-sabahs-status-dashed-to-the-ground-by-gps-sabah-opposition-mps/|archivedate=10 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Despite the failure of the bill passage, Minister Liew has stated that they would never give up and would continue to fight for the people especially for those in the two entities,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bharian.com.my/berita/nasional/2019/04/551995/usaha-pinda-perlembagaan-persekutuan-diteruskan|title=Usaha pinda Perlembagaan Persekutuan diteruskan|trans-title=Efforts for the amendment of the Constitution will continued|author=Amin Ridzuan Ishak|language=Malay|publisher=Berita Harian|date=12 April 2019|accessdate=15 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190415034004/https://www.bharian.com.my/berita/nasional/2019/04/551995/usaha-pinda-perlembagaan-persekutuan-diteruskan|archive-date=15 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> calling the action by a small group of parliamentarians not voting for the amendment was unreasonable and detrimental to the society with the moment will forever be remembered and identified by the generation as those who preventing the return of the two entities status.<ref name=\"failure of passage forever remembered in history\"/>\n\nGPS through its SUPP President Sim Kui Hian said the blame should not been thrown on them, but instead the federal government should have listened earlier to their demands to amend the definition of the \"federation\" as a federation that were established through the 1963 agreement, not under the federation term as inscribed in the 1957 Malaya Agreement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/04/10/dont-blame-gps-for-defeat-of-sarawak-status-amendment-bill-says-supp-presid/1741857|title=Don't blame GPS for defeat of Sarawak status amendment Bill, says SUPP president|author=Sulok Tawie|publisher=The Malay Mail|date=10 April 2019|accessdate=10 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190410111722/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/04/10/dont-blame-gps-for-defeat-of-sarawak-status-amendment-bill-says-supp-presid/1741857|archivedate=10 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> STAR Sarawak President Lina Soo called the failure to pass the bill as a \"landmark victory\" for Sarawakians and Sabahans, praising that the political maturity of the people in the two entities has reached new heights which is not seen since the formation of the country.<ref name=\"landmark win\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thesundaily.my/local/landmark-win-for-sabah-sarawak-in-bill-amendment-failure-says-star-YC774643|title=Landmark win for Sabah, Sarawak in Bill amendment failure, says STAR|work=The Borneo Post|publisher=The Sun|date=10 April 2019|accessdate=10 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190410104830/https://www.thesundaily.my/local/landmark-win-for-sabah-sarawak-in-bill-amendment-failure-says-star-YC774643|archivedate=10 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> She adding that the people had voiced out loud and clear that any constitutional amendment without adhering to the principle of the 1963 agreement must be rejected where she also insisted that any constitutional amendment which would have subsequent effect to the political position of the two entities must first be brought before the current state legislative assembly for legitimacy.<ref name=\"landmark win\"/> Responding to the \"landmark victory\" as claimed by opposition allied parties, Sabah [[Beluran (federal constituency)|Beluran]] MP Ronald Kiandee described the move by the opposition as just to politicising the issue too much with their abstention from the bill voting just for the sake of opposing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2019/04/10/opposition-opposed-amendment-bill-for-the-sake-of-opposing-says-sabah-mp/|title=Opposition opposed amendment bill for the sake of opposing, says Sabah MP|author=Minderjeet Kaur|publisher=Free Malaysia Today|date=10 April 2019|accessdate=10 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190410110643/https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2019/04/10/opposition-opposed-amendment-bill-for-the-sake-of-opposing-says-sabah-mp/|archivedate=10 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Former law lecturer [[Abdul Aziz Bari]] also said those opposition MPs who didn't vote for the amendment bill could have actually used their debate time to point out what they saw as lacking in it and ask for the gaps to be filled, calling the suggestion made by an opposition MP from [[Pengerang (federal constituency)|Pengerang]], [[Azalina Othman Said]] for the need of a select committee before the bill tabling are actually just to wasting the time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2019/04/11/azalina-spewing-nonsense-on-constitutional-amendment-bill-says-law-expert/|title=Azalina spewing nonsense on constitutional amendment bill, says law expert|author=Vinodh Pillai|publisher=Free Malaysia Today|date=11 April 2019|accessdate=11 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190411081031/https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2019/04/11/azalina-spewing-nonsense-on-constitutional-amendment-bill-says-law-expert/|archivedate=11 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The adviser of the Sabah government on the 1963 agreement, Zainnal Ajamain said following the result, the two entities lost their opportunity to restore their status as equal partners. In a statement, he said:\n\n{{cquote|We know that in the first reading there are problems, but in the second reading [the content] is taken from {{abbr|MA63|the 1963 Malaysia Agreement}}, word by word, unchanged \u2026 then it was also rejected. [The defeat of the amendment] has big implications. We have been waiting for 55 years, then we have this rare opportunity. The opportunity is there, but some people are still dissatisfied \u2026 It's up to them. I think the dissatisfied party should now think deeply, to reflect on what has happened and read as well understand [the 1963 agreement] better.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/04/11/sabah-sarawak-miss-opportunity-to-restore-status-as-equal-partners/|title=Sabah, Sarawak miss opportunity to restore status as equal partners|work=Bernama|publisher=The Borneo Post|date=11 April 2019|accessdate=11 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190411030026/https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/04/11/sabah-sarawak-miss-opportunity-to-restore-status-as-equal-partners/|archivedate=11 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>}}\n\nAn independent Sabah MP, Anifah Aman stated that even the Parliament failed to pass the bill, the fight for equal partnership will never end.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2019/04/478082/sabah-lawmakers-will-not-stop-finding-ways-restore-equal-partnership|title=Sabah lawmakers will not stop finding ways to restore equal partnership for the state|author=Olivia Miwil|publisher=New Straits Times|date=10 April 2019|accessdate=10 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190410105841/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2019/04/478082/sabah-lawmakers-will-not-stop-finding-ways-restore-equal-partnership|archive-date=10 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The leader of the opposition, Ismail Sabri Yaakob stressed that even the opposition choose to abstained in the voting, the bill are not actually lost since not even a single opposition MPs rejecting the bill, adding that the federal government should not have been rushed for its tabling in the Parliament but instead taken it up for a thorough discussion at the parliamentary select committee as if the joint committee have expressing their views along with their facts, both can jointly support the amendment since he himself also questioned the amendment bid's significance to the two entities which according to him would only highlight the difference between those in the peninsula and those in Borneo from a geographical perspective.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/04/10/bill-on-sabah-sarawak-should-go-through-psc-first-says-ismail-sabri/1741756|title=Bill on Sabah, Sarawak should go through PSC first, says Ismail Sabri|author=Terence Tang|publisher=The Malay Mail|date=10 April 2019|accessdate=11 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190411031239/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/04/10/bill-on-sabah-sarawak-should-go-through-psc-first-says-ismail-sabri/1741756|archivedate=11 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Similar opinion were also expressed by an UMNO Supreme Council Member and former MP [[Abdul Rahman Dahlan]] who said that he did not blame the Prime Minister for what has happened as the bill was originally drafted by Minister Liew who failed to understand what opposition MPs from the two entities really wanted with regard to the amendment, adding that if the bill was earlier sent to the select committee, it surely be a win-win situation for all concerned parties with the Prime Minister would receive praises from all quarters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/04/11/minister-failed-to-understand-what-sabah-sarawak-mps-want-rahman/|title=Minister failed to understand what Sabah, Sarawak MPs want \u2013 Rahman|publisher=The Borneo Post|date=11 April 2019|accessdate=11 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190411032018/https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/04/11/minister-failed-to-understand-what-sabah-sarawak-mps-want-rahman/|archivedate=11 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Similar views were expressed by Sarawak Chief Minister Abang Abdul Rahman Zohari.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/04/12/sarawak-cm-secretariat-weakness-caused-sabah-sarawak-amendment-bill-to-fail/1742657|title=Abang Johari: Secretariat weakness caused Constitution amendment Bill to fail|publisher=The Malay Mail|date=12 April 2019|accessdate=13 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190413034301/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/04/12/sarawak-cm-secretariat-weakness-caused-sabah-sarawak-amendment-bill-to-fail/1742657|archivedate=13 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Another opposition MP of MCA from [[Ayer Hitam (federal constituency)|Ayer Hitam]], [[Wee Ka Siong]] said the proposed bill is done in rush and merely a cosmetic change, stressing that the opposition only want the bill to be looked into carefully and diligently for the constitutional amendment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2019/04/11/wee-it-was-a-rush-job-and-merely-a-cosmetic-change/|title=Wee: It was a rush job and merely a cosmetic change|work=The Star|date=11 April 2019|accessdate=11 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190411093916/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2019/04/11/wee-it-was-a-rush-job-and-merely-a-cosmetic-change/|archive-date=11 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Nevertheless, with the unaccomplished goals, Sabah Deputy Chief Minister Wilfred Madius Tangau hopes the steering committee on the 1963 agreement chaired by the Prime Minister would meet as soon as possible to further discuss steps that will be taken by the Sabah government.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/04/10/sabah-dcm-wants-ma63-steering-committee-to-meet-with-haste/|title=Sabah DCM wants MA63 Steering Committee to meet with haste|author=Nancy Lai|publisher=The Borneo Post|date=10 April 2019|accessdate=11 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190411045820/https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/04/10/sabah-dcm-wants-ma63-steering-committee-to-meet-with-haste/|archivedate=11 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On the proposal to re-tabling the bill in the Parliament as the bill should be referred first to a special committee, Prime Minister Mahathir answered the question that a discussion will be held with involved MPs on the matter with the re-tabling would depend on \"needs\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pmo.gov.my/2019/04/re-tabling-of-amendment-bill-depends-on-needs-pm/|title=Re-Tabling of Amendment Bill Depends on Needs \u2013 PM|work=Bernama|publisher=Prime Minister's Department (Malaysia)|date=10 April 2019|accessdate=15 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190415034019/https://www.pmo.gov.my/2019/04/re-tabling-of-amendment-bill-depends-on-needs-pm/|archivedate=15 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/133683/re-tabling-of-bill-depends-pm/|title=Re-tabling of Bill depends: PM|work=Bernama|publisher=Daily Express|date=11 April 2019|accessdate=11 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190411053837/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/133683/re-tabling-of-bill-depends-pm/|archivedate=11 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Sabah State Legislative Assembly|Sabah Legislative Assembly]] through Chief Minister Shafie had announced they would table emergency motion regarding the 1963 agreement in the nearest time to regain their rights despite the bill failure following the request made by one of the assemblyman, Masidi Manjun.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2019/04/15/sabah-reps-urged-to-show-support-for-bill-shot-down-in-dewan-rakyat/|title=Sabah reps urged to show support for bill shot down in Dewan Rakyat|author=Durie Rainer Fong|publisher=Free Malaysia Today|date=15 April 2019|accessdate=16 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416060815/https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2019/04/15/sabah-reps-urged-to-show-support-for-bill-shot-down-in-dewan-rakyat/|archivedate=15 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/04/15/sabah-cm-says-would-table-urgent-motion-on-ma63/1743390|title=Sabah CM says would table urgent motion on MA63|author=Julia Chan|publisher=The Malay Mail|date=15 April 2019|accessdate=16 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416055752/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/04/15/sabah-cm-says-would-table-urgent-motion-on-ma63/1743390|archivedate=15 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/133927/sabah-s-dues-to-be-pursued/|title=Sabah's dues to be pursued|author=Ricardo Unto|publisher=Daily Express|date=16 April 2019|accessdate=16 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416055855/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/133927/sabah-s-dues-to-be-pursued/|archivedate=15 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On 18 April, the Sabah assembly unanimously passed a motion to endorse the proposed amendment if it gets re-tabled in the national Parliament.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2019/04/18/sabah-assembly-endorses-amendment-of-constitution-to-honour-ma63/|title=Sabah assembly endorses amendment of Constitution to honour MA63|author=Kristy Inus|work=The Star|date=18 April 2019|accessdate=20 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190420041313/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2019/04/18/sabah-assembly-endorses-amendment-of-constitution-to-honour-ma63/|archive-date=20 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://dailyexpress.com.my/news/134069/unanimous-assembly-support-for-restoring-sabah-s-status/|title=Unanimous Assembly support for restoring Sabah's status|author=Leonard Alaza|publisher=Daily Express|date=19 April 2019|accessdate=20 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190420041032/http://dailyexpress.com.my/news/134069/unanimous-assembly-support-for-restoring-sabah-s-status/|archivedate=20 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Sarawak State Legislative Assembly|Sarawak Legislative Assembly]] follow suits on 30 April by unanimously approves motion for constitutional amendments on Sarawak's rights with the motion includes a provision for the amendment of Article 1(2) of the Federal Constitution by inserting \"pursuant to Malaysia Agreement 1963\" which subsequently read as: \"The States of the Federation, pursuant to Malaysian Agreement 1963, shall be\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/04/30/sarawak-assembly-unanimously-approves-motion-for-constitutional-amendments/1748532|title=Sarawak Assembly unanimously approves motion for constitutional amendments on state's rights|author=Sulok Tawie|publisher=The Malay Mail|date=30 April 2019|accessdate=13 July 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190712233335/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/04/30/sarawak-assembly-unanimously-approves-motion-for-constitutional-amendments/1748532|archivedate=13 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nLocal analysts hold the view that the failure for the bill passage is not end on the struggle of both entities to restore their status, urging both sides of political factions either from the government and opposition to stop blaming each other and moving forwards towards a solution for the betterment of the residents in the two entities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/metro/metro-news/2019/04/13/stop-the-blame-game-and-try-again/|title=Stop the blame game and try again|author=Sharon Ling|work=The Star|date=13 April 2019|accessdate=13 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190413071049/https://www.thestar.com.my/metro/metro-news/2019/04/13/stop-the-blame-game-and-try-again/|archive-date=13 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Other political analysts also in the position that the opposition faction of GPS did not simply want the bill to fail, but instead just want to ensure it is done correctly, adding that despite the bill failure, the federal government must move forward to correct the long historical grievances in the two entities before it is escalated into far more [[secession]]ist option with the growing frustration and unhappiness.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/opinion/columnists/its-just-politics/2019/04/14/leaving-is-getting-sexy-for-some/|title='Leaving' is getting sexy for some|author=Philip Golingai|work=The Star|date=14 April 2019|accessdate=14 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190414133855/https://www.thestar.com.my/opinion/columnists/its-just-politics/2019/04/14/leaving-is-getting-sexy-for-some/|archive-date=14 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2019/04/15/failure-to-amend-constitution-leaves-lingering-divisions/|title=Failure to amend constitution leaves lingering divisions|author=Durie Rainer Fong|publisher=Free Malaysia Today|date=15 April 2019|accessdate=15 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190415085519/https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2019/04/15/failure-to-amend-constitution-leaves-lingering-divisions/|archivedate=15 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDuring the celebration of [[Sarawak Day]] on 22 July, Sarawak Association for People's Aspiration (SAPA) reminded the federal government to not wasting further time to restore Sarawak's rights and status under the 1963 agreement with the increase independence sentiment among the people.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2019/07/22/ngo-restore-sarawak-rights-or-risk-a-secession-movement/|title=NGO: Restore Sarawak rights or risk a secession movement|author=Sharon Ling|work=The Star|date=22 July 2019|accessdate=25 July 2019}}</ref> Further on 25 July, Sabah Chief Minister Shafie said that Prime Minister Mahathir will announce the restoration of both Sabah and Sarawak rights in the nearest time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/07/25/sabah-cm-pm-set-to-announce-restoration-of-states-rights-soon/1774712|title=Sabah CM: PM set to announce restoration of state's rights soon|author=Julia Chan|publisher=The Malay Mail|date=25 July 2019|accessdate=25 July 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190725111754/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/07/25/sabah-cm-pm-set-to-announce-restoration-of-states-rights-soon/1774712|archivedate=25 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On 17 December, Minister Liew announced that the proposed amendment to be re-tabled in March 2020 following a reach consensus through a three-way meeting between Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad, Sabah Chief Minister Shafie Apdal and Sarawak Chief Minister Abang Zohari held at the Prime Minister's office on 16 December 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/12/17/amendment-to-restore-sabah-sarawaks-status-to-be-tabled-in-march-2020/|title=Amendment to restore Sabah, Sarawak\u2019s status to be tabled in March 2020|work=Bernama|publisher=The Borneo Post|date=17 December 2019|accessdate=19 December 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191219060518/https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/12/17/amendment-to-restore-sabah-sarawaks-status-to-be-tabled-in-march-2020/|archivedate=19 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of amendments to the Constitution of Malaysia]]\n* [[List of active separatist movements in Asia#Malaysia|Separatist movements of Malaysia]]\n* [[History of the Republic of Singapore#Expulsion from Malaysia|Separation of Singapore from Malaysia]]\n\n{{Portal bar|Law|Malaysia}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n== Footnotes and references ==\n{{reflist|24em}}\n\n=== Print ===\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Silcock\n  | first = Thomas Henry\n  | year = 1963\n  | url = https://archive.org/details/politicaleconomy0000silc\n  | url-access = registration\n  | page = [https://archive.org/details/politicaleconomy0000silc/page/53 53]\n  | quote = borneo special rights.\n  | title = The Political Economy of Independent Malaya: A Case-study in Development\n  | publisher = University of California Press\n  | id = GGKEY:LTF1ABP2J6P\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Wilson\n  | first = L. S.\n  | year = 1996\n  | url = https://archive.org/details/federalstatefisc0000wils\n  | url-access = registration\n  | quote = sabah 40% state revenue.\n  | title = Federal-state fiscal arrangements in Malaysia ; State revenue equalization in Malaysia\n  | publisher = Queen's University, John Deutsch Institute for the Study of Economic Policy\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last1 = Chin\n  | first1 = Anthony\n  | last2 = Choi\n  | first2 = Alfred\n  | year = 1998\n  | title = Law, Social Sciences, and Public Policy: Towards a Unified Framework\n  | publisher = NUS Press\n  | isbn = 978-9971-69-205-6\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Hashim\n  | first = Shireen Mardziah\n  | year = 1998\n  | title = Income Inequality and Poverty in Malaysia\n  | publisher = Rowman & Littlefield\n  | isbn = 978-0-8476-8858-6\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Sadiq\n  | first = Kamal\n  | year = 2008\n  | title = Paper Citizens: How Illegal Immigrants Acquire Citizenship in Developing Countries\n  | publisher = Oxford University Press\n  | isbn = 978-0-19-988813-9\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Lim\n  | first = Regina\n  | year = 2008\n  | title = Federal-state Relations in Sabah, Malaysia: The Berjaya Administration, 1976-85\n  | publisher = Institute of Southeast Asian Studies\n  | isbn = 978-981-230-812-2\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last1 = Dambul\n  | first1 = Ramzah\n  | last2 = Omar\n  | first2 = Marja Azlima\n  | last3 = Osman\n  | first3 = Sabihah\n  | year = 2010\n  | url = https://books.google.com/?id=IdFRAQAAMAAJ&q=RM5+billion+per+year+SABAH&dq=RM5+billion+per+year+SABAH\n  | title = Sabah Priority Issues: Setting the Course for Change\n  | publisher = Universiti Malaysia Sabah\n  | isbn = 978-967-5224-45-4\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Harding\n  | first = Andrew\n  | year = 2012\n  | title = The Constitution of Malaysia: A Contextual Analysis\n  | publisher = Bloomsbury Publishing\n  | isbn = 978-1-84731-983-8\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last1 = Harding\n  | first1 = Andrew J.\n  | last2 = Chin\n  | first2 = James\n  | year = 2014\n  | title = 50 Years of Malaysia: Federalism Revisited\n  | publisher = Marshall Cavendish International Asia Pte Ltd\n  | isbn = 978-981-4561-96-9\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Weiss\n  | first = Meredith L.\n  | year = 2014\n  | title = Routledge Handbook of Contemporary Malaysia\n  | publisher = Taylor & Francis\n  | isbn = 978-1-317-62958-0\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Kaur\n  | first = A.\n  | year = 2016\n  | title = Economic Change in East Malaysia: Sabah and Sarawak since 1850\n  | publisher = Palgrave Macmillan UK\n  | isbn = 978-0-230-37709-7\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Popelier\n  | first = Patricia\n  | year = 2019\n  | title = Constitutional Asymmetry in Multinational Federalism: Managing\n  | publisher = Springer\n  | isbn = 978-3-030-11701-6\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n{{refend}}\n\n=== Further reading ===\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://says.com/my/lifestyle/formation-of-malaysia-old-photos-malaysia-agreement-1963|title=The Historical Moments That Led Up To Malaysia's Formation, Captured In 35 Old Photos|author=Tang Ruxyn|publisher=Says.com|date=15 September 2017}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://asklegal.my/p/5-facts-about-the-malaysia-agreement-1963|title=5 Facts You Didn't Know About The Malaysia Agreement 1963|author=Fadzel|publisher=AskLegal|year=2017}}\n* {{cite journal|url=https://www.academia.edu/37322619|title=Why new Malaysian govt must heed MA63 rallying cry|author=James Chin|journal=The Straits Times|via=Academia.edu|date=31 May 2018}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/opinion/columnists/2018/09/413924/restoring-sabah-and-sarawaks-lost-rights|title=Restoring Sabah and Sarawak's lost rights|author=John Teo|publisher=New Straits Times|date=22 September 2018}}\n* {{cite journal|url=https://www.academia.edu/38119476|title=Sabah and Sarawak in the 14th General Election 2018 (GE14): Local Factors and State Nationalism|author=James Chin|journal=Journal of Current Southeast Asian Affairs|via=Academia.edu|date=19 November 2018|volume=37|pages=173\u2013192|number=3|doi=10.1177/186810341803700308}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/01/27/protecting-special-rights-of-borneo-territories/|title=Protecting special rights of Borneo Territories|author=Alex Ling|publisher=The Borneo Post|date=27 January 2019}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/02/24/necessary-amendments-of-the-fc-and-federal-acts/|title=Necessary amendments of the FC and Federal Acts|author=Alex Ling|publisher=The Borneo Post|date=24 February 2019}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.worldofbuzz.com/status-update-sabah-sarawak-will-no-longer-be-treated-like-any-other-states-in-peninsula/|title=Status Update: Sabah & Sarawak Will No Longer Be Treated like Any Other States in Peninsula|author=Alief Esmail|publisher=World of Buzz|date=10 March 2019}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/04/07/necessary-amendments-on-the-territorial-sea-eez-and-continental-shelf-of-sarawak-and-sabah/|title=Necessary amendments on the Territorial Sea, EEZ and Continental Shelf of Sarawak and Sabah|author=Alex Ling|publisher=The Borneo Post|date=7 April 2019}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/opinion/back-to-the-future-for-east-malaysia|title=Back to the future for East Malaysia?|author=Joseph Chinyong Liow|publisher=The Straits Times|date=9 April 2019|url-access=subscription}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/commentary/sarawak-sabah-malaysia-bill-secession-ma63-sarexit-11428822|title=Commentary: The ghost of Borneo, talk of secession are back to haunt Malaysia|author=James Chin|publisher=Channel NewsAsia|date=10 April 2019}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.mysinchew.com/node/121259|title=Restore Sabah, Sarawak as equal partners|publisher=Sin Chew Daily|date=11 April 2019}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/futile-bid-for-equal-partner-status-evokes-passion-in-sabah-sarawak|title=Futile bid for 'equal partner' status evokes passion in Sabah, Sarawak|author=Eileen Ng|publisher=The Straits Times|date=22 April 2019|url-access=subscription}}\n{{div col end}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20190404080654/http://www.agc.gov.my/agcportal/uploads/files/Publications/FC/Federal%20Consti%20(BI%20text).pdf Constitution of Malaysia (as of 2010)]\n\n{{History of East Malaysia}}\n\n[[Category:Failed amendments of the Constitution of Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Formation of Malaysia]]\n[[Category:History of Malaysia]]\n", "name_user": "Kaltenmeyer", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBreaches of the Malaysia Agreement:clean up, replaced: incorpoat \u2192 incorporat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proposed_2019_amendment_to_the_Constitution_of_Malaysia"}
